WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.425 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.425 --> 00:00:04.365 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.365 --> 00:00:06.305 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:06.305 --> 00:00:10.300 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.300 --> 00:00:15.320 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: OK, so
let me just recall first

00:00:15.320 --> 00:00:21.920 align:middle line:84%
that we were talking about
a very important concept

00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:25.440 align:middle line:84%
of a sequence,
concept of a sequence.

00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:30.520 align:middle line:84%
So a sequence, the
formal definition

00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:39.100 align:middle line:84%
is that you have a map from
the natural number into R.

00:00:39.100 --> 00:00:43.800 align:middle line:84%
So then the image of a
particular natural number n,

00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:47.660 align:middle line:84%
it's usually denoted
like an, like this.

00:00:47.660 --> 00:00:51.280 align:middle line:84%
It could be some other
instead of a, it could be bn.

00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:53.660 align:middle line:84%
Potentially, it could
be another subscript.

00:00:53.660 --> 00:00:58.800 align:middle line:84%
But this is the most common
thing to denote it like this.

00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:01.130 align:middle line:90%
But it really is a function.

00:01:01.130 --> 00:01:02.430 align:middle line:90%
So that's a sequence.

00:01:02.430 --> 00:01:07.370 align:middle line:90%


00:01:07.370 --> 00:01:11.490 align:middle line:84%
So a subsequence is
that you have a sequence

00:01:11.490 --> 00:01:14.010 align:middle line:90%
and then you have another map.

00:01:14.010 --> 00:01:18.690 align:middle line:84%
But this map is not just
any map from the integers

00:01:18.690 --> 00:01:19.850 align:middle line:90%
to the integers.

00:01:19.850 --> 00:01:22.030 align:middle line:84%
It has to be
strictly increasing.

00:01:22.030 --> 00:01:25.410 align:middle line:90%


00:01:25.410 --> 00:01:27.690 align:middle line:84%
And why does it have to
be strictly increasing?

00:01:27.690 --> 00:01:31.290 align:middle line:84%
Because we want,
for the subsequence,

00:01:31.290 --> 00:01:34.690 align:middle line:84%
if you think about the
numbers that come out

00:01:34.690 --> 00:01:39.170 align:middle line:84%
when you plug in a, when
you're looking at the an,

00:01:39.170 --> 00:01:42.850 align:middle line:84%
then you want some
of those numbers

00:01:42.850 --> 00:01:44.470 align:middle line:90%
to be in the subsequence.

00:01:44.470 --> 00:01:48.070 align:middle line:84%
But you want the
ordering to be the same.

00:01:48.070 --> 00:01:52.890 align:middle line:84%
So that's why this map has
to be strictly increasing.

00:01:52.890 --> 00:01:56.650 align:middle line:84%
You can't pick the several
elements many times

00:01:56.650 --> 00:01:59.950 align:middle line:84%
if it wasn't picked many times
in the original sequence.

00:01:59.950 --> 00:02:03.620 align:middle line:90%


00:02:03.620 --> 00:02:07.440 align:middle line:84%
So a subsequence
is where you have

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:09.500 align:middle line:84%
another map from
the natural number

00:02:09.500 --> 00:02:12.340 align:middle line:84%
to the natural number that
is strictly increasing.

00:02:12.340 --> 00:02:16.100 align:middle line:84%
And then you're looking at the
composition of these two maps.

00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:21.000 align:middle line:84%
So you're looking
at this in here.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:22.780 align:middle line:90%
And you call this here.

00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:29.580 align:middle line:84%
And then that's usually
denoted something like this--

00:02:29.580 --> 00:02:31.780 align:middle line:90%
ank.

00:02:31.780 --> 00:02:34.980 align:middle line:84%
An is the original
sequence, k means

00:02:34.980 --> 00:02:37.940 align:middle line:84%
that it's really that
you take the image of k

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:40.380 align:middle line:84%
under this strictly
increasing map.

00:02:40.380 --> 00:02:43.300 align:middle line:84%
And then you're looking at
the element in the sequence.

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:51.580 align:middle line:84%
So, nk, really, you should
think about it as g of k.

00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:56.290 align:middle line:90%
So that's what a subsequence is.

00:02:56.290 --> 00:02:58.790 align:middle line:84%
And again, it's important
that it's strictly

00:02:58.790 --> 00:03:02.990 align:middle line:84%
increasing because you want the
elements to be in the same order

00:03:02.990 --> 00:03:05.190 align:middle line:84%
than it was in the
original sequence.

00:03:05.190 --> 00:03:10.362 align:middle line:84%
And you don't even want things
to be picked more times than it

00:03:10.362 --> 00:03:11.570 align:middle line:90%
was in the original sequence.

00:03:11.570 --> 00:03:15.550 align:middle line:90%


00:03:15.550 --> 00:03:19.470 align:middle line:84%
So this whole concept of
a sequence and subsequence

00:03:19.470 --> 00:03:21.110 align:middle line:90%
is really important.

00:03:21.110 --> 00:03:31.390 align:middle line:84%
Then, the next really important
concept is of convergence.

00:03:31.390 --> 00:03:34.230 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a
sequence an, then

00:03:34.230 --> 00:03:36.490 align:middle line:84%
you say that it's
converging to a.

00:03:36.490 --> 00:03:39.190 align:middle line:90%
So a is another real number.

00:03:39.190 --> 00:03:40.270 align:middle line:90%
It's not infinity.

00:03:40.270 --> 00:03:42.310 align:middle line:90%
It's another real number.

00:03:42.310 --> 00:03:56.360 align:middle line:84%
And so an converges to a if
for all epsilon greater than 0,

00:03:56.360 --> 00:04:06.000 align:middle line:84%
there exist N, an integer
N, denoted by capital N,

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:11.920 align:middle line:84%
such that if little n is bigger
or equal to this capital N, then

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:21.640 align:middle line:84%
an minus a have to
be less than epsilon.

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:25.440 align:middle line:84%
So if you are sufficiently
far out in the sequence,

00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:31.640 align:middle line:84%
then everything in that sequence
is bunched epsilon close to n.

00:04:31.640 --> 00:04:34.000 align:middle line:90%
That's what it's saying.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:50.840 align:middle line:84%
And so if you have a sequence, a
sequence that is not convergent,

00:04:50.840 --> 00:04:52.990 align:middle line:90%
it is said to be divergent.

00:04:52.990 --> 00:05:03.214 align:middle line:90%


00:05:03.214 --> 00:05:09.330 align:middle line:84%
And the next thing,
I'm just briefly

00:05:09.330 --> 00:05:12.810 align:middle line:84%
reviewing this from last time--
the next thing for sequences

00:05:12.810 --> 00:05:25.230 align:middle line:84%
are the algebraic laws or
whatever you want to call them.

00:05:25.230 --> 00:05:27.810 align:middle line:90%


00:05:27.810 --> 00:05:31.090 align:middle line:84%
And so that is that if
you take a sequence,

00:05:31.090 --> 00:05:40.370 align:middle line:84%
if you have a sequence an and an
converts to a, bn converts to b,

00:05:40.370 --> 00:05:46.010 align:middle line:84%
then if you form the
sum of these two,

00:05:46.010 --> 00:05:52.140 align:middle line:84%
an plus bn, so this is
a new sequence where

00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:55.300 align:middle line:84%
the n-th element is the
sum of the n-th element

00:05:55.300 --> 00:05:57.500 align:middle line:90%
of the other two sequences.

00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:01.060 align:middle line:84%
Then this sequence
here cn also converges.

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:06.486 align:middle line:84%
And the limit here is
the sum of the limits.

00:06:06.486 --> 00:06:16.740 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, if you define
a sequence-- so this was 1--

00:06:16.740 --> 00:06:19.540 align:middle line:84%
2 is that if you
take a constant.

00:06:19.540 --> 00:06:22.420 align:middle line:90%
So this is a constant.

00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:29.460 align:middle line:84%
And you define cn to be c times
an, then this cn also converge.

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:34.000 align:middle line:84%
And the limit here
is just c times a.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.160 align:middle line:90%
That's the second one.

00:06:37.160 --> 00:06:38.880 align:middle line:84%
I might have done it
in the other order.

00:06:38.880 --> 00:06:48.990 align:middle line:84%
But there's no particular
order to have it in.

00:06:48.990 --> 00:06:53.810 align:middle line:84%
The third one is that if you
are looking at the products.

00:06:53.810 --> 00:06:55.590 align:middle line:84%
So if you define
a sequence that is

00:06:55.590 --> 00:07:01.430 align:middle line:84%
given by the product of the
two, then cn converge also.

00:07:01.430 --> 00:07:05.670 align:middle line:84%
And the limit is the
product of the limits.

00:07:05.670 --> 00:07:13.430 align:middle line:84%
And then the fourth rule is
that if an is not equal to 0

00:07:13.430 --> 00:07:20.910 align:middle line:84%
for all n and the limit
here is also not equal to 0,

00:07:20.910 --> 00:07:25.470 align:middle line:84%
then if you're looking at 1 over
an, then those converge to 1

00:07:25.470 --> 00:07:27.830 align:middle line:90%
over a.

00:07:27.830 --> 00:07:32.030 align:middle line:90%
So those are the four rules.

00:07:32.030 --> 00:07:34.510 align:middle line:90%
Let me just write it as 4.

00:07:34.510 --> 00:07:37.270 align:middle line:84%
And again, it's not like there's
any particular convention

00:07:37.270 --> 00:07:38.410 align:middle line:90%
with the ordering.

00:07:38.410 --> 00:07:42.390 align:middle line:84%
And I think I might have
exchanged the order of 1 and 2

00:07:42.390 --> 00:07:43.170 align:middle line:90%
last time.

00:07:43.170 --> 00:07:48.760 align:middle line:90%


00:07:48.760 --> 00:07:52.690 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's see an example
of how that works.

00:07:52.690 --> 00:07:58.480 align:middle line:90%


00:07:58.480 --> 00:08:04.920 align:middle line:84%
Let's define a sequence
n squared plus 1,

00:08:04.920 --> 00:08:10.760 align:middle line:90%
n squared plus n plus 1.

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:14.320 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at this sequence
here for each n that

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:19.840 align:middle line:84%
gives us, actually, a rational
number, but it's a real number.

00:08:19.840 --> 00:08:22.520 align:middle line:84%
Now in order to
understand this, I

00:08:22.520 --> 00:08:31.160 align:middle line:84%
can rewrite this one here, as I
can factor out n squared here.

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:32.620 align:middle line:90%
So I can write it like this.

00:08:32.620 --> 00:08:44.049 align:middle line:90%


00:08:44.049 --> 00:08:44.710 align:middle line:90%
Like that.

00:08:44.710 --> 00:08:46.170 align:middle line:84%
And then, of course,
I can get rid

00:08:46.170 --> 00:08:51.230 align:middle line:84%
of the n squared in both
numerator and denominator.

00:08:51.230 --> 00:08:53.750 align:middle line:90%


00:08:53.750 --> 00:08:56.790 align:middle line:84%
So you may as well think about
the sequence as this thing here.

00:08:56.790 --> 00:09:00.470 align:middle line:90%


00:09:00.470 --> 00:09:10.890 align:middle line:84%
So now, I can just first look at
the sequence which is 1 over n.

00:09:10.890 --> 00:09:15.690 align:middle line:84%
If I'm looking at this
sequence here, 1 over n, this

00:09:15.690 --> 00:09:17.390 align:middle line:90%
here converges to 0.

00:09:17.390 --> 00:09:20.150 align:middle line:84%
This essentially just follows
from the Archimedean property.

00:09:20.150 --> 00:09:26.530 align:middle line:84%
But we've already seen this,
that 1 over n converges to 0.

00:09:26.530 --> 00:09:30.690 align:middle line:84%
And the same holds
for 1 over n squared.

00:09:30.690 --> 00:09:33.810 align:middle line:90%
This also converges to 0.

00:09:33.810 --> 00:09:36.690 align:middle line:84%
And so if you're
looking at the sequence,

00:09:36.690 --> 00:09:42.500 align:middle line:84%
you could even look at the
sequence, let's call this xn.

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:44.020 align:middle line:90%
This here is yn.

00:09:44.020 --> 00:09:48.700 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to run out of
character very quickly, zn.

00:09:48.700 --> 00:09:53.380 align:middle line:84%
This is just going to be the
sequence, which is constant 1.

00:09:53.380 --> 00:09:59.060 align:middle line:84%
Well, if it's constant 1, then
obviously it's converging to 1.

00:09:59.060 --> 00:10:06.060 align:middle line:84%
So now I can think
about the sequence being

00:10:06.060 --> 00:10:18.140 align:middle line:84%
to be equal to z
plus y, zn plus yn.

00:10:18.140 --> 00:10:20.040 align:middle line:90%
This here is a sequence.

00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:21.860 align:middle line:90%
Here is what yn is.

00:10:21.860 --> 00:10:23.900 align:middle line:90%
Here is what is zn is.

00:10:23.900 --> 00:10:28.060 align:middle line:84%
So if you add these two,
this is converging to 1.

00:10:28.060 --> 00:10:30.220 align:middle line:90%
This is converging to 0.

00:10:30.220 --> 00:10:32.940 align:middle line:84%
By the algebraic
property of limits,

00:10:32.940 --> 00:10:36.160 align:middle line:84%
this converge also to
the sum of the limit.

00:10:36.160 --> 00:10:38.540 align:middle line:90%
So this converges to 1.

00:10:38.540 --> 00:10:42.310 align:middle line:84%
Now, I can also
define a sequence

00:10:42.310 --> 00:10:47.630 align:middle line:84%
where I'm just adding zn
and then I'm adding xn

00:10:47.630 --> 00:10:48.870 align:middle line:90%
and then I'm adding yn.

00:10:48.870 --> 00:10:52.812 align:middle line:90%


00:10:52.812 --> 00:10:58.310 align:middle line:84%
This here converges to 1, this
here to 0, this here to 0.

00:10:58.310 --> 00:11:02.850 align:middle line:84%
So the sum here also converge
to the sum of the limit.

00:11:02.850 --> 00:11:04.690 align:middle line:90%
But the sum of the limit is 1.

00:11:04.690 --> 00:11:16.430 align:middle line:90%


00:11:16.430 --> 00:11:17.250 align:middle line:90%
Put it up here.

00:11:17.250 --> 00:11:21.410 align:middle line:90%
And then I'll just go over here.

00:11:21.410 --> 00:11:24.070 align:middle line:90%


00:11:24.070 --> 00:11:33.230 align:middle line:84%
So now you have that
cn converge to 1.

00:11:33.230 --> 00:11:35.710 align:middle line:90%
And let's call this c.

00:11:35.710 --> 00:11:40.920 align:middle line:84%
And so, in particular,
all of these numbers here,

00:11:40.920 --> 00:11:43.180 align:middle line:84%
these things here are
all strictly positive.

00:11:43.180 --> 00:11:45.500 align:middle line:84%
So each of the cn's
are strictly positive.

00:11:45.500 --> 00:11:47.800 align:middle line:90%
So they're definitely not 0.

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:51.720 align:middle line:84%
So the cn, so not only
do they converge to 1,

00:11:51.720 --> 00:11:54.440 align:middle line:90%
but the cn's are not equal to 0.

00:11:54.440 --> 00:11:57.380 align:middle line:90%
And the limit c, well, that's 1.

00:11:57.380 --> 00:12:00.330 align:middle line:84%
So that's, of course,
not equal to 0 either.

00:12:00.330 --> 00:12:03.760 align:middle line:84%
So you can apply the
fourth rule here.

00:12:03.760 --> 00:12:10.480 align:middle line:84%
The fourth rule for the
sequence, for the sequence cn,

00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:13.600 align:middle line:84%
so applying the fourth
rule to the sequence cn,

00:12:13.600 --> 00:12:18.360 align:middle line:84%
and then you have that 1
over cn converge to 1 over c,

00:12:18.360 --> 00:12:21.200 align:middle line:90%
but c was 1, so this is 1.

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:24.160 align:middle line:90%


00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:33.720 align:middle line:84%
Now you can look at
bn times 1 over cn.

00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:37.130 align:middle line:90%
But bn times 1 over cn--

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:38.950 align:middle line:90%
remember what bn was.

00:12:38.950 --> 00:12:40.570 align:middle line:90%
Here's bn.

00:12:40.570 --> 00:12:44.890 align:middle line:84%
And bn is really the
numerator up here.

00:12:44.890 --> 00:12:46.890 align:middle line:84%
It's the numerator
up here when you

00:12:46.890 --> 00:12:51.970 align:middle line:84%
have divided by
n squared on both

00:12:51.970 --> 00:12:54.450 align:middle line:90%
in the top and the numerator.

00:12:54.450 --> 00:13:00.070 align:middle line:84%
So bn is the numerator
and cn is the denominator.

00:13:00.070 --> 00:13:05.690 align:middle line:90%
So bn divided by cn, this is an.

00:13:05.690 --> 00:13:08.310 align:middle line:90%
And now this here converge.

00:13:08.310 --> 00:13:10.050 align:middle line:90%
That's what we saw over there.

00:13:10.050 --> 00:13:13.530 align:middle line:84%
Using the algebraic
rule, it converges to 1.

00:13:13.530 --> 00:13:18.570 align:middle line:84%
This here also converge to
1 by the algebraic rules.

00:13:18.570 --> 00:13:22.410 align:middle line:84%
Number 3 of the algebraic
rules is that for the product

00:13:22.410 --> 00:13:24.330 align:middle line:90%
it will also converge.

00:13:24.330 --> 00:13:27.970 align:middle line:84%
And it converges to the
product of the limits.

00:13:27.970 --> 00:13:28.890 align:middle line:90%
So that's 1.

00:13:28.890 --> 00:13:31.410 align:middle line:90%


00:13:31.410 --> 00:13:36.560 align:middle line:84%
Obviously, this is like when
you're looking at a sequence,

00:13:36.560 --> 00:13:40.260 align:middle line:84%
it's often expressed
in some form

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:43.940 align:middle line:90%
with some functions like this.

00:13:43.940 --> 00:13:46.580 align:middle line:90%
And you do this reduction.

00:13:46.580 --> 00:13:50.280 align:middle line:84%
And very quickly, this
would be almost automatic.

00:13:50.280 --> 00:13:53.260 align:middle line:84%
This is too easy
almost, this one.

00:13:53.260 --> 00:13:54.900 align:middle line:84%
This is the first
time you see it,

00:13:54.900 --> 00:13:58.940 align:middle line:84%
but you know in a couple of
weeks this will feel too easy.

00:13:58.940 --> 00:14:01.360 align:middle line:84%
Then there will be
something more complicated.

00:14:01.360 --> 00:14:05.524 align:middle line:90%


00:14:05.524 --> 00:14:11.780 align:middle line:84%
So that's the algebraic
rules for sequences.

00:14:11.780 --> 00:14:13.540 align:middle line:84%
The next thing I
want to talk about

00:14:13.540 --> 00:14:19.940 align:middle line:84%
is, I want to try to make more
precise this about square.

00:14:19.940 --> 00:14:22.470 align:middle line:84%
We made it pretty precise,
but I want to think about--

00:14:22.470 --> 00:14:25.180 align:middle line:90%


00:14:25.180 --> 00:14:28.380 align:middle line:84%
I don't have a very good
eraser, unfortunately.

00:14:28.380 --> 00:14:29.740 align:middle line:90%
Let me just see.

00:14:29.740 --> 00:14:33.097 align:middle line:90%
This is a better one.

00:14:33.097 --> 00:14:34.680 align:middle line:84%
This one here will
make it very dirty.

00:14:34.680 --> 00:14:38.630 align:middle line:90%


00:14:38.630 --> 00:14:44.050 align:middle line:84%
So the next thing, we did
define square root of 2.

00:14:44.050 --> 00:14:46.270 align:middle line:84%
And we talked about
that quite extensively,

00:14:46.270 --> 00:14:50.770 align:middle line:84%
how square root of 2, how
it really was defined.

00:14:50.770 --> 00:14:52.410 align:middle line:90%
And it was a real number.

00:14:52.410 --> 00:14:57.910 align:middle line:84%
And the real numbers followed
from that, the field,

00:14:57.910 --> 00:15:01.350 align:middle line:90%
the reals is complete.

00:15:01.350 --> 00:15:08.670 align:middle line:84%
But we also, in the
back of our mind,

00:15:08.670 --> 00:15:13.190 align:middle line:84%
we had that we already sort
of knew what square root of 2

00:15:13.190 --> 00:15:17.030 align:middle line:84%
were because when you think
about square root of 2, at least

00:15:17.030 --> 00:15:20.930 align:middle line:84%
I think about square root of
2, I think about it as 1.4.

00:15:20.930 --> 00:15:24.030 align:middle line:84%
Just because you can't really
express it as a fraction.

00:15:24.030 --> 00:15:27.810 align:middle line:84%
So you think about it
as 1.414, et cetera.

00:15:27.810 --> 00:15:31.140 align:middle line:84%
And then I don't remember the
second, third, and fourth,

00:15:31.140 --> 00:15:31.640 align:middle line:90%
whatever.

00:15:31.640 --> 00:15:34.826 align:middle line:84%
But you may remember
just a few of the digits.

00:15:34.826 --> 00:15:39.680 align:middle line:90%


00:15:39.680 --> 00:15:44.560 align:middle line:84%
So that's sort of our
intuition with 1.4--

00:15:44.560 --> 00:15:46.920 align:middle line:90%
with square root 2.

00:15:46.920 --> 00:15:49.720 align:middle line:84%
But how do we make
this more precise?

00:15:49.720 --> 00:15:53.920 align:middle line:84%
And so to make
this more precise,

00:15:53.920 --> 00:15:58.800 align:middle line:84%
we want to look at
particular sequences, what's

00:15:58.800 --> 00:16:02.800 align:middle line:90%
called monotone sequences.

00:16:02.800 --> 00:16:07.080 align:middle line:90%


00:16:07.080 --> 00:16:10.440 align:middle line:90%
So what is a monotone sequence?

00:16:10.440 --> 00:16:13.300 align:middle line:84%
So there are two types
of monotone sequences.

00:16:13.300 --> 00:16:16.410 align:middle line:84%
There's one which is
monotone increasing sequence.

00:16:16.410 --> 00:16:26.320 align:middle line:90%


00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:31.210 align:middle line:84%
And then there's, similarly,
monotone decreasing sequence.

00:16:31.210 --> 00:16:33.710 align:middle line:84%
So a monotone
increasing sequence,

00:16:33.710 --> 00:16:41.210 align:middle line:84%
this just means
that for all n, you

00:16:41.210 --> 00:16:45.450 align:middle line:84%
have that the next
element is larger

00:16:45.450 --> 00:16:48.290 align:middle line:84%
or equal to the
previous element.

00:16:48.290 --> 00:16:51.530 align:middle line:84%
That's a monotone
increasing sequence.

00:16:51.530 --> 00:16:54.910 align:middle line:84%
Some people talk about
strictly monotone increasing--

00:16:54.910 --> 00:16:57.467 align:middle line:84%
and then this has to
be a strict inequality.

00:16:57.467 --> 00:17:01.290 align:middle line:90%


00:17:01.290 --> 00:17:04.450 align:middle line:84%
The second thing is
kind of the obvious.

00:17:04.450 --> 00:17:11.470 align:middle line:84%
Parallel to this is monotone
decreasing sequences.

00:17:11.470 --> 00:17:17.730 align:middle line:90%


00:17:17.730 --> 00:17:19.609 align:middle line:90%
So there's these two types.

00:17:19.609 --> 00:17:25.050 align:middle line:84%
And this just means that the
next element, so an plus 1

00:17:25.050 --> 00:17:28.319 align:middle line:84%
is less than or equal
to the previous one.

00:17:28.319 --> 00:17:33.788 align:middle line:90%


00:17:33.788 --> 00:17:37.060 align:middle line:90%
And so now there's a theorem.

00:17:37.060 --> 00:17:39.530 align:middle line:84%
And I'll prove this
in just a minute.

00:17:39.530 --> 00:17:43.100 align:middle line:90%


00:17:43.100 --> 00:17:45.940 align:middle line:84%
And I want to come back
to square root of 2.

00:17:45.940 --> 00:17:51.060 align:middle line:84%
And then I want to look at
another classical example

00:17:51.060 --> 00:17:52.290 align:middle line:90%
of a monotone sequence.

00:17:52.290 --> 00:17:59.400 align:middle line:90%


00:17:59.400 --> 00:18:01.040 align:middle line:90%
So this is a monotone sequence.

00:18:01.040 --> 00:18:03.910 align:middle line:84%
And now let me state the
monotone convergence theorem.

00:18:03.910 --> 00:18:17.415 align:middle line:90%


00:18:17.415 --> 00:18:18.790 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
following theorem.

00:18:18.790 --> 00:18:24.820 align:middle line:90%


00:18:24.820 --> 00:18:26.910 align:middle line:84%
And there's two
versions of this.

00:18:26.910 --> 00:18:29.890 align:middle line:84%
There's one version for
monotone increasing sequence.

00:18:29.890 --> 00:18:32.982 align:middle line:84%
And then there's one version for
monotone decreasing sequence.

00:18:32.982 --> 00:18:35.190 align:middle line:84%
I'll just state one of them,
because the other one is

00:18:35.190 --> 00:18:37.190 align:middle line:90%
kind of obviously a parallel.

00:18:37.190 --> 00:18:48.270 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that an is
a monotone increasing

00:18:48.270 --> 00:18:57.640 align:middle line:90%
sequence that is bounded.

00:18:57.640 --> 00:19:01.350 align:middle line:90%


00:19:01.350 --> 00:19:08.150 align:middle line:84%
Bounded, so this just means
that there exists, i.e.

00:19:08.150 --> 00:19:21.610 align:middle line:84%
there exists some a, real
number, so that you have a1.

00:19:21.610 --> 00:19:24.080 align:middle line:90%
This says that it's monotone.

00:19:24.080 --> 00:19:26.280 align:middle line:84%
This is monotone
that they increase.

00:19:26.280 --> 00:19:30.960 align:middle line:84%
But the claim is that
now all of the an

00:19:30.960 --> 00:19:35.200 align:middle line:90%
is less than or equal to this a.

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:38.920 align:middle line:84%
Any monotone increasing sequence
is clearly bounded from below

00:19:38.920 --> 00:19:44.360 align:middle line:84%
because already the first
element is a lower bound.

00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:51.840 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a monotone
increasing sequence that is

00:19:51.840 --> 00:20:14.880 align:middle line:84%
bounded, then it's convergent
and with limit a, where a is

00:20:14.880 --> 00:20:17.640 align:middle line:90%
the sup of the an's.

00:20:17.640 --> 00:20:28.690 align:middle line:90%


00:20:28.690 --> 00:20:34.730 align:middle line:84%
So that is a monotone
convergence sequence.

00:20:34.730 --> 00:20:39.730 align:middle line:84%
And the main theorem about
monotone convergence sequence

00:20:39.730 --> 00:20:42.690 align:middle line:84%
is that if you have
a monotone increasing

00:20:42.690 --> 00:20:47.690 align:middle line:84%
sequence that is bounded,
then it's also convergent.

00:20:47.690 --> 00:20:51.290 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, if you have
a monotone decreasing

00:20:51.290 --> 00:20:56.490 align:middle line:84%
sequence that is
bounded from below,

00:20:56.490 --> 00:20:59.330 align:middle line:90%
then it is also convergent.

00:20:59.330 --> 00:21:03.370 align:middle line:90%
And so maybe I will state it.

00:21:03.370 --> 00:21:04.920 align:middle line:84%
But it's just the
obvious parallel.

00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:09.382 align:middle line:90%


00:21:09.382 --> 00:21:14.580 align:middle line:84%
So this is part 1 of the
monotone convergence sequence.

00:21:14.580 --> 00:21:18.050 align:middle line:90%


00:21:18.050 --> 00:21:33.860 align:middle line:84%
Part B is that if an is
a monotone decreasing

00:21:33.860 --> 00:21:51.140 align:middle line:84%
sequence that is
bounded from below,

00:21:51.140 --> 00:22:00.940 align:middle line:84%
then an is convergent with
limit a, where a is now

00:22:00.940 --> 00:22:04.370 align:middle line:90%
the inf of these numbers.

00:22:04.370 --> 00:22:16.150 align:middle line:90%


00:22:16.150 --> 00:22:19.910 align:middle line:84%
Now, the first thing
you might say--

00:22:19.910 --> 00:22:22.210 align:middle line:84%
and we'll come to square
root of 2 in just a minute--

00:22:22.210 --> 00:22:24.970 align:middle line:84%
but you may say that this
seems rather special.

00:22:24.970 --> 00:22:30.150 align:middle line:84%
If you take a random
sequence, obviously, it's

00:22:30.150 --> 00:22:31.656 align:middle line:90%
not going to be monotone.

00:22:31.656 --> 00:22:36.590 align:middle line:90%


00:22:36.590 --> 00:22:39.430 align:middle line:90%
But here's the thing.

00:22:39.430 --> 00:22:47.100 align:middle line:84%
So let an be any
bounded sequence.

00:22:47.100 --> 00:22:56.390 align:middle line:90%


00:22:56.390 --> 00:22:59.110 align:middle line:84%
So bounded, again, means
that it's bounded from above

00:22:59.110 --> 00:23:00.910 align:middle line:90%
and bounded from below.

00:23:00.910 --> 00:23:05.070 align:middle line:84%
So if you take any
bounded sequence,

00:23:05.070 --> 00:23:15.682 align:middle line:84%
then we can form
two other sequences.

00:23:15.682 --> 00:23:17.140 align:middle line:84%
Obviously, we can
form many others.

00:23:17.140 --> 00:23:21.380 align:middle line:84%
But here's two other
very natural sequences.

00:23:21.380 --> 00:23:24.480 align:middle line:90%


00:23:24.480 --> 00:23:27.840 align:middle line:90%
The first one I call bn.

00:23:27.840 --> 00:23:41.920 align:middle line:84%
And bn is the sup, where
you're starting at an,

00:23:41.920 --> 00:23:45.200 align:middle line:84%
then you take the sup
of all of the ones

00:23:45.200 --> 00:23:49.612 align:middle line:84%
from an and outwards
in the sequence.

00:23:49.612 --> 00:23:54.220 align:middle line:90%
So this is one sequence.

00:23:54.220 --> 00:23:58.900 align:middle line:84%
We know that the set
of an's is bounded.

00:23:58.900 --> 00:24:03.180 align:middle line:84%
So you can certainly take the
sup, and you get a real number.

00:24:03.180 --> 00:24:05.880 align:middle line:90%
That gives you another sequence.

00:24:05.880 --> 00:24:08.720 align:middle line:84%
You can also look
at cn similarly,

00:24:08.720 --> 00:24:10.640 align:middle line:84%
where you take
instead of the sup,

00:24:10.640 --> 00:24:20.730 align:middle line:84%
you take the inf of the
same set, like that.

00:24:20.730 --> 00:24:24.170 align:middle line:84%
And so in particular,
just to make sure

00:24:24.170 --> 00:24:34.410 align:middle line:84%
it's totally clear that if
you were looking at, say, bn,

00:24:34.410 --> 00:24:35.930 align:middle line:90%
so what is bn?

00:24:35.930 --> 00:24:39.090 align:middle line:84%
If you're looking at,
say, b3, then this

00:24:39.090 --> 00:24:47.770 align:middle line:84%
is the sup where you're
starting at a3, a4, et cetera.

00:24:47.770 --> 00:24:52.170 align:middle line:84%
And so you see, of
course, that b3 here,

00:24:52.170 --> 00:24:57.850 align:middle line:84%
well, obviously, b3 is
bigger or equal to b2--

00:24:57.850 --> 00:25:03.050 align:middle line:90%


00:25:03.050 --> 00:25:05.090 align:middle line:84%
sorry, no, it's not
bigger or equal to,

00:25:05.090 --> 00:25:08.490 align:middle line:84%
it's less than or equal
to b2 because, you

00:25:08.490 --> 00:25:14.660 align:middle line:84%
see, in b2, the definition of
b2, so let's just write b2 down.

00:25:14.660 --> 00:25:23.992 align:middle line:84%
So b2 is when you take the sup
here of a2 and then a3, a4, et

00:25:23.992 --> 00:25:26.540 align:middle line:90%
cetera.

00:25:26.540 --> 00:25:29.060 align:middle line:90%
But you see that b2 here--

00:25:29.060 --> 00:25:31.420 align:middle line:84%
both of them are
defined to be sup--

00:25:31.420 --> 00:25:36.500 align:middle line:84%
but b2 is defined as
sup over a larger set

00:25:36.500 --> 00:25:42.380 align:middle line:84%
because, in addition to these
elements, it also includes a2.

00:25:42.380 --> 00:25:48.940 align:middle line:84%
So clearly, b2 here is
bigger or equal to b3.

00:25:48.940 --> 00:26:00.900 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, the same argument
tells you that if you take bn,

00:26:00.900 --> 00:26:06.540 align:middle line:84%
bn is bigger or
equal to bn plus 1

00:26:06.540 --> 00:26:11.870 align:middle line:84%
because this here is the
sup over a larger set.

00:26:11.870 --> 00:26:18.030 align:middle line:84%
It's sup over all the ones
you take sup in here, plus an.

00:26:18.030 --> 00:26:21.590 align:middle line:90%
So you have this property here.

00:26:21.590 --> 00:26:22.350 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:26:22.350 --> 00:26:24.505 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: When you say that the
[INAUDIBLE] sup over a larger

00:26:24.505 --> 00:26:24.990 align:middle line:90%
set--

00:26:24.990 --> 00:26:25.350 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah.

00:26:25.350 --> 00:26:27.267 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The way that
I was thinking about it

00:26:27.267 --> 00:26:31.030 align:middle line:84%
is, like, well, if it
said monotone increasing--

00:26:31.030 --> 00:26:33.990 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: If it's
monotone increasing,

00:26:33.990 --> 00:26:40.590 align:middle line:84%
then this here, then it
becomes very special.

00:26:40.590 --> 00:26:48.630 align:middle line:84%
So if the an was monotone
increasing, then all of these,

00:26:48.630 --> 00:26:52.850 align:middle line:84%
any elements here, would just
be the a we talked about before.

00:26:52.850 --> 00:26:56.070 align:middle line:90%
It would always be the limit.

00:26:56.070 --> 00:27:01.010 align:middle line:84%
So it somehow wouldn't be
that interesting a sequence.

00:27:01.010 --> 00:27:02.750 align:middle line:90%
It would be a constant sequence.

00:27:02.750 --> 00:27:04.390 align:middle line:90%
And it would be just the limit.

00:27:04.390 --> 00:27:05.390 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: OK, thank you.

00:27:05.390 --> 00:27:08.030 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: But
nevertheless, it's

00:27:08.030 --> 00:27:09.445 align:middle line:90%
a good example.

00:27:09.445 --> 00:27:11.840 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: But I guess the
inequality still holds, then.

00:27:11.840 --> 00:27:12.560 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING:
Yeah, definitely,

00:27:12.560 --> 00:27:14.400 align:middle line:84%
because it's just
constant, exactly.

00:27:14.400 --> 00:27:14.960 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah, of course.

00:27:14.960 --> 00:27:16.460 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING:
It's a good example.

00:27:16.460 --> 00:27:19.120 align:middle line:84%
But it's just kind of
almost like too simple

00:27:19.120 --> 00:27:23.280 align:middle line:84%
because you get a
constant sequence, right?

00:27:23.280 --> 00:27:28.340 align:middle line:84%
OK, so for this sequence
that we defined, so we have,

00:27:28.340 --> 00:27:32.360 align:middle line:84%
again, if you take
any sequence, then

00:27:32.360 --> 00:27:36.040 align:middle line:84%
you have two
sequences bn and cn.

00:27:36.040 --> 00:27:41.080 align:middle line:84%
And bn here is now a
decreasing sequence.

00:27:41.080 --> 00:27:44.940 align:middle line:84%
And instead of writing
decreasing sequence,

00:27:44.940 --> 00:27:49.720 align:middle line:84%
then it's much easier
to write it like this.

00:27:49.720 --> 00:27:51.170 align:middle line:90%
This is pretty standard.

00:27:51.170 --> 00:27:54.040 align:middle line:90%


00:27:54.040 --> 00:27:57.600 align:middle line:84%
If you just look quickly at
it, you know what this means.

00:27:57.600 --> 00:28:00.160 align:middle line:90%
You don't have to write it out.

00:28:00.160 --> 00:28:03.600 align:middle line:90%
But let's look at cn also.

00:28:03.600 --> 00:28:08.910 align:middle line:84%
Remember that we assume that
an could be any sequence,

00:28:08.910 --> 00:28:11.290 align:middle line:84%
but it is supposed
to be bounded.

00:28:11.290 --> 00:28:15.250 align:middle line:84%
So this is now a monotone
decreasing sequence

00:28:15.250 --> 00:28:16.390 align:middle line:90%
that is bounded.

00:28:16.390 --> 00:28:17.630 align:middle line:90%
So it actually has a limit.

00:28:17.630 --> 00:28:20.330 align:middle line:90%


00:28:20.330 --> 00:28:22.340 align:middle line:90%
The cn's, what about the cn's?

00:28:22.340 --> 00:28:28.130 align:middle line:90%


00:28:28.130 --> 00:28:36.810 align:middle line:84%
The cn's, well, cn was
defined to be the inf starting

00:28:36.810 --> 00:28:39.796 align:middle line:90%
at an like that.

00:28:39.796 --> 00:28:45.522 align:middle line:90%


00:28:45.522 --> 00:28:49.130 align:middle line:84%
So if you're starting
like that, this

00:28:49.130 --> 00:28:56.070 align:middle line:84%
means that if you take cn plus
1, then you take the infimum,

00:28:56.070 --> 00:28:59.470 align:middle line:84%
but you don't
include this element.

00:28:59.470 --> 00:29:02.690 align:middle line:84%
So it's an infimum
over fewer elements.

00:29:02.690 --> 00:29:08.500 align:middle line:84%
But then this n must be
larger or equal to that.

00:29:08.500 --> 00:29:14.740 align:middle line:84%
So you see that the
sequence cn is monotone

00:29:14.740 --> 00:29:17.300 align:middle line:90%
increasing again, is bounded.

00:29:17.300 --> 00:29:22.760 align:middle line:84%
And just copying from over
there, the bn was decreasing.

00:29:22.760 --> 00:29:27.280 align:middle line:90%


00:29:27.280 --> 00:29:29.300 align:middle line:90%
This is an important thing.

00:29:29.300 --> 00:29:31.060 align:middle line:84%
It's also something
that you would

00:29:31.060 --> 00:29:33.700 align:middle line:84%
see in a lot of
different contexts

00:29:33.700 --> 00:29:37.600 align:middle line:84%
where you define something,
some sort of something,

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:40.420 align:middle line:90%
and then you have this property.

00:29:40.420 --> 00:29:46.240 align:middle line:84%
And so now the thing is that if
you're looking at, so a priori,

00:29:46.240 --> 00:29:48.820 align:middle line:84%
it might not be so
clear to compare

00:29:48.820 --> 00:29:50.580 align:middle line:84%
a random element
in this sequence

00:29:50.580 --> 00:29:52.540 align:middle line:90%
to a random element in that.

00:29:52.540 --> 00:30:03.310 align:middle line:84%
But what is clear is that if
you try to compare bn with cn,

00:30:03.310 --> 00:30:05.510 align:middle line:90%
it's the same set.

00:30:05.510 --> 00:30:06.950 align:middle line:90%
It's the same set.

00:30:06.950 --> 00:30:09.990 align:middle line:84%
In one, you take the sup,
the other you take the inf.

00:30:09.990 --> 00:30:14.370 align:middle line:84%
So of course bn is
bigger or equal to cn.

00:30:14.370 --> 00:30:15.870 align:middle line:90%
So you have this, right?

00:30:15.870 --> 00:30:19.310 align:middle line:84%
And so now you see that if
you take like a random element

00:30:19.310 --> 00:30:28.650 align:middle line:84%
here, if it was like further
out, if it was cn, further out,

00:30:28.650 --> 00:30:31.370 align:middle line:84%
I just write it as
something further out.

00:30:31.370 --> 00:30:33.750 align:middle line:84%
So you're adding
something else to it.

00:30:33.750 --> 00:30:35.910 align:middle line:84%
So this would be
like further out.

00:30:35.910 --> 00:30:39.590 align:middle line:84%
We know that this
sequence here--

00:30:39.590 --> 00:30:41.230 align:middle line:90%
anyway, so you get--

00:30:41.230 --> 00:30:47.010 align:middle line:84%
sorry, now you're getting
this here like that.

00:30:47.010 --> 00:30:50.030 align:middle line:90%


00:30:50.030 --> 00:30:52.870 align:middle line:90%
And so you have this.

00:30:52.870 --> 00:30:57.190 align:middle line:84%
What I should have done is
that this sequence here, so

00:30:57.190 --> 00:31:00.230 align:middle line:90%
let me draw it like this.

00:31:00.230 --> 00:31:05.080 align:middle line:84%
So I have that,
here is maybe c1.

00:31:05.080 --> 00:31:09.240 align:middle line:90%
Here is b1.

00:31:09.240 --> 00:31:16.360 align:middle line:84%
And now the next element,
the sequence cn is increasing

00:31:16.360 --> 00:31:21.440 align:middle line:84%
and the sequence
bn is decreasing.

00:31:21.440 --> 00:31:23.520 align:middle line:90%
But you always have this here.

00:31:23.520 --> 00:31:28.040 align:middle line:84%
So c2 have to lie to
the right of this.

00:31:28.040 --> 00:31:32.000 align:middle line:84%
But it has to lie
to the left of b2.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:34.560 align:middle line:90%
So you're getting this here.

00:31:34.560 --> 00:31:40.840 align:middle line:84%
So you see that this gives you a
way to compare that the cn will

00:31:40.840 --> 00:31:44.080 align:middle line:84%
always lie to the
left of the bn's.

00:31:44.080 --> 00:31:47.000 align:middle line:90%


00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:55.280 align:middle line:84%
So now what we have done here
is we took any bounded sequence

00:31:55.280 --> 00:31:59.558 align:middle line:84%
and we formed two
monotone sequences.

00:31:59.558 --> 00:32:01.630 align:middle line:90%
They are both monotone.

00:32:01.630 --> 00:32:08.570 align:middle line:90%


00:32:08.570 --> 00:32:11.810 align:middle line:84%
So this means that now from the
monotone convergence that we

00:32:11.810 --> 00:32:17.210 align:middle line:84%
haven't quite proven yet, but
from the monotone convergence

00:32:17.210 --> 00:32:20.170 align:middle line:84%
theorem, because
these are bounded,

00:32:20.170 --> 00:32:26.690 align:middle line:90%
we have that bn are converging.

00:32:26.690 --> 00:32:27.880 align:middle line:90%
They're going down.

00:32:27.880 --> 00:32:29.190 align:middle line:90%
So they're converging.

00:32:29.190 --> 00:32:32.410 align:middle line:84%
So one often would write it
like this more suggestively.

00:32:32.410 --> 00:32:37.290 align:middle line:84%
That is converging
downwards to a limit b.

00:32:37.290 --> 00:32:42.430 align:middle line:84%
And the cn is converging
upwards to a limit c.

00:32:42.430 --> 00:32:45.690 align:middle line:90%


00:32:45.690 --> 00:32:49.630 align:middle line:84%
And so what you get is because
of all of these elements,

00:32:49.630 --> 00:32:54.370 align:middle line:84%
all the cn's lie to
the left of the bn's.

00:32:54.370 --> 00:32:57.960 align:middle line:84%
This means that, and
we'll prove this later,

00:32:57.960 --> 00:33:02.500 align:middle line:84%
but it seems probably pretty
obvious that the limit here, c

00:33:02.500 --> 00:33:04.200 align:middle line:90%
is less than or equal to b.

00:33:04.200 --> 00:33:07.160 align:middle line:90%


00:33:07.160 --> 00:33:09.650 align:middle line:84%
So we'll come back to
this also next time.

00:33:09.650 --> 00:33:13.580 align:middle line:90%


00:33:13.580 --> 00:33:15.220 align:middle line:84%
If I have time, I'll
talk a little bit

00:33:15.220 --> 00:33:16.900 align:middle line:90%
about Cauchy sequence.

00:33:16.900 --> 00:33:19.430 align:middle line:84%
But I won't really
prove too much about it.

00:33:19.430 --> 00:33:23.260 align:middle line:84%
But this here will
play an important role

00:33:23.260 --> 00:33:29.700 align:middle line:84%
when we prove the basic
theorem about Cauchy sequences.

00:33:29.700 --> 00:33:35.060 align:middle line:84%
The takeaway here at
the moment is just,

00:33:35.060 --> 00:33:39.740 align:middle line:84%
you have this concept of a
monotone either increasing

00:33:39.740 --> 00:33:41.740 align:middle line:90%
or decreasing sequence.

00:33:41.740 --> 00:33:45.480 align:middle line:84%
If such a sequence is
bounded, then it's convergent.

00:33:45.480 --> 00:33:47.900 align:middle line:84%
That's a monotone
convergence theorem.

00:33:47.900 --> 00:33:53.840 align:middle line:84%
And again, for any sequence,
any bounded sequence,

00:33:53.840 --> 00:33:57.390 align:middle line:84%
there's a very natural
monotone increasing sequence

00:33:57.390 --> 00:33:59.800 align:middle line:84%
and a very natural monotone
decreasing sequence.

00:33:59.800 --> 00:34:04.030 align:middle line:90%


00:34:04.030 --> 00:34:08.409 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's try to prove the
monotone convergence theorem.

00:34:08.409 --> 00:34:13.550 align:middle line:84%
And then let's get back how to
think about square root of 2

00:34:13.550 --> 00:34:16.250 align:middle line:84%
in a more intuitive
way using this.

00:34:16.250 --> 00:34:28.670 align:middle line:90%


00:34:28.670 --> 00:34:32.530 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now the proof of the
monotone convergence theorem.

00:34:32.530 --> 00:34:54.560 align:middle line:90%


00:34:54.560 --> 00:34:58.120 align:middle line:84%
So now let me just
remind you what we have.

00:34:58.120 --> 00:35:02.240 align:middle line:84%
So I'm only going to prove
one of the two versions of it

00:35:02.240 --> 00:35:04.520 align:middle line:84%
where the sequence is
monotone increasing

00:35:04.520 --> 00:35:09.640 align:middle line:84%
because the other
one is just the same

00:35:09.640 --> 00:35:13.320 align:middle line:90%
with obvious modifications.

00:35:13.320 --> 00:35:17.080 align:middle line:90%
So this is the assumption.

00:35:17.080 --> 00:35:18.460 align:middle line:90%
So this is assumption.

00:35:18.460 --> 00:35:24.760 align:middle line:90%


00:35:24.760 --> 00:35:29.640 align:middle line:84%
So this is just that the
next element is larger

00:35:29.640 --> 00:35:31.400 align:middle line:90%
or equal to the previous one.

00:35:31.400 --> 00:35:35.880 align:middle line:84%
And they're all
bounded by this a.

00:35:35.880 --> 00:35:46.980 align:middle line:84%
Now, we set little a equal
to the sup of the an.

00:35:46.980 --> 00:35:59.110 align:middle line:90%


00:35:59.110 --> 00:36:10.290 align:middle line:84%
We want to show that
an converts to a.

00:36:10.290 --> 00:36:15.670 align:middle line:84%
Now to do that what we need is
we need this stuff about that,

00:36:15.670 --> 00:36:22.010 align:middle line:84%
for a given epsilon,
there exists a capital N.

00:36:22.010 --> 00:36:37.050 align:middle line:84%
So now let me first make
the observation that a here,

00:36:37.050 --> 00:36:41.880 align:middle line:90%
since a here is the sup--

00:36:41.880 --> 00:36:50.980 align:middle line:90%


00:36:50.980 --> 00:36:55.460 align:middle line:84%
remember that the sup of a set
is the smallest upper bound.

00:36:55.460 --> 00:37:00.620 align:middle line:90%


00:37:00.620 --> 00:37:03.760 align:middle line:84%
So a is, in particular,
an upper bound.

00:37:03.760 --> 00:37:11.900 align:middle line:84%
So you have that an is
less than a for all n,

00:37:11.900 --> 00:37:15.820 align:middle line:90%
since a is an upper bound.

00:37:15.820 --> 00:37:17.480 align:middle line:84%
It's actually the
smallest upper bound.

00:37:17.480 --> 00:37:19.590 align:middle line:84%
But for this you just
need it's an upper bound.

00:37:19.590 --> 00:37:32.940 align:middle line:90%


00:37:32.940 --> 00:37:35.190 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to look at a minus an.

00:37:35.190 --> 00:37:37.740 align:middle line:90%


00:37:37.740 --> 00:37:41.660 align:middle line:84%
And what I want to prove is
that for a given epsilon,

00:37:41.660 --> 00:37:47.020 align:middle line:84%
if I'm sufficiently
far out, if little n is

00:37:47.020 --> 00:37:51.350 align:middle line:84%
bigger than some capital N, then
this here is less than epsilon.

00:37:51.350 --> 00:37:52.910 align:middle line:90%
That's what I want to prove.

00:37:52.910 --> 00:37:55.570 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here,
you see this here,

00:37:55.570 --> 00:37:58.350 align:middle line:84%
I don't need the absolute
value because I already know

00:37:58.350 --> 00:37:59.730 align:middle line:90%
that this is bigger than that.

00:37:59.730 --> 00:38:02.990 align:middle line:84%
So I don't need
the absolute value.

00:38:02.990 --> 00:38:05.070 align:middle line:90%
So this is what I want to prove.

00:38:05.070 --> 00:38:10.110 align:middle line:84%
I want to prove that given
epsilon greater than 0,

00:38:10.110 --> 00:38:10.700 align:middle line:90%
they exists--

00:38:10.700 --> 00:38:13.830 align:middle line:90%


00:38:13.830 --> 00:38:16.270 align:middle line:84%
let me just write a
little larger here.

00:38:16.270 --> 00:38:21.590 align:middle line:84%
So what I want to prove is that
given epsilon greater than 0,

00:38:21.590 --> 00:38:32.430 align:middle line:84%
there exists a capital N such
that if little n is bigger

00:38:32.430 --> 00:38:36.990 align:middle line:84%
or equal to this capital N,
then a minus an, which I know

00:38:36.990 --> 00:38:39.750 align:middle line:84%
is positive, I
just need to prove

00:38:39.750 --> 00:38:41.080 align:middle line:90%
that this is less than epsilon.

00:38:41.080 --> 00:38:47.320 align:middle line:90%


00:38:47.320 --> 00:38:49.120 align:middle line:90%
So now how do we do that?

00:38:49.120 --> 00:38:58.260 align:middle line:84%
Well, at the moment I've just
used that a was an upper bound.

00:38:58.260 --> 00:39:01.840 align:middle line:84%
Now I'm going to use that
as the least upper bound.

00:39:01.840 --> 00:39:15.800 align:middle line:84%
So since a is the
least upper bound,

00:39:15.800 --> 00:39:24.200 align:middle line:84%
then a minus epsilon
is not an upper bound.

00:39:24.200 --> 00:39:32.385 align:middle line:90%


00:39:32.385 --> 00:39:35.300 align:middle line:84%
a minus epsilon is
not an upper bound.

00:39:35.300 --> 00:39:37.150 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
there must exist--

00:39:37.150 --> 00:39:39.920 align:middle line:90%


00:39:39.920 --> 00:39:50.180 align:middle line:84%
there exists a capital N so
that an is bigger or equal--

00:39:50.180 --> 00:39:53.580 align:middle line:84%
so capital N, just
this one here,

00:39:53.580 --> 00:39:57.340 align:middle line:84%
is bigger than a minus
epsilon because otherwise, it

00:39:57.340 --> 00:39:59.620 align:middle line:90%
would have been an upper bound.

00:39:59.620 --> 00:40:01.460 align:middle line:90%
But it's actually strictly.

00:40:01.460 --> 00:40:04.740 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I should write
strictly because else

00:40:04.740 --> 00:40:05.880 align:middle line:90%
would have [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:05.880 --> 00:40:09.700 align:middle line:90%


00:40:09.700 --> 00:40:15.100 align:middle line:84%
But I already know that this
thing here is less than a.

00:40:15.100 --> 00:40:17.846 align:middle line:90%


00:40:17.846 --> 00:40:21.500 align:middle line:84%
And also, in fact, I
know more than this.

00:40:21.500 --> 00:40:26.660 align:middle line:84%
I know that this thing here is
less than or equal to a little n

00:40:26.660 --> 00:40:30.580 align:middle line:84%
as long as little n is bigger
than capital N. That was just

00:40:30.580 --> 00:40:32.780 align:middle line:84%
because the sequence
was increasing.

00:40:32.780 --> 00:40:37.420 align:middle line:84%
And all of them is smaller
than this upper bound.

00:40:37.420 --> 00:40:42.560 align:middle line:84%
So now you see, so
here you have a,

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:46.990 align:middle line:84%
all the elements
an lie to the left.

00:40:46.990 --> 00:40:51.630 align:middle line:84%
And if you're looking at
just the one from a capital

00:40:51.630 --> 00:40:55.670 align:middle line:84%
N outwards, then here
you have a minus epsilon.

00:40:55.670 --> 00:41:00.110 align:middle line:84%
And then they lie between
this one here and that.

00:41:00.110 --> 00:41:03.110 align:middle line:84%
In particular, they lie
to the right of this

00:41:03.110 --> 00:41:04.790 align:middle line:90%
and to the left of that.

00:41:04.790 --> 00:41:06.590 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
they're squished

00:41:06.590 --> 00:41:09.630 align:middle line:90%
in this little interval.

00:41:09.630 --> 00:41:13.550 align:middle line:84%
So this difference here, this
difference from here to here

00:41:13.550 --> 00:41:16.430 align:middle line:84%
is certainly bounded
by the distance

00:41:16.430 --> 00:41:17.740 align:middle line:90%
to here, which was epsilon.

00:41:17.740 --> 00:41:21.400 align:middle line:90%


00:41:21.400 --> 00:41:25.060 align:middle line:84%
So this proves that this thing
here is less than epsilon.

00:41:25.060 --> 00:41:28.355 align:middle line:90%


00:41:28.355 --> 00:41:33.310 align:middle line:84%
And, well, an obvious
modification--

00:41:33.310 --> 00:41:36.450 align:middle line:90%
the proof that if you take--

00:41:36.450 --> 00:41:39.270 align:middle line:84%
so this was an
increasing sequence--

00:41:39.270 --> 00:41:43.760 align:middle line:84%
the proof that if you have
a decreasing sequence that

00:41:43.760 --> 00:41:49.120 align:middle line:84%
is bounded, that the
limit of that is the inf,

00:41:49.120 --> 00:41:54.620 align:middle line:84%
the proof with obvious
changes is the same.

00:41:54.620 --> 00:41:59.470 align:middle line:90%


00:41:59.470 --> 00:42:03.240 align:middle line:84%
So now let's come back
to square root of 2.

00:42:03.240 --> 00:42:07.280 align:middle line:84%
And so we have this
idea that square root 2,

00:42:07.280 --> 00:42:14.720 align:middle line:84%
in a way, the way to just get
an idea about how large it is,

00:42:14.720 --> 00:42:18.580 align:middle line:84%
you think about it as 1 and then
a number of digits afterwards.

00:42:18.580 --> 00:42:20.540 align:middle line:90%
That's a kind of approximation.

00:42:20.540 --> 00:42:23.412 align:middle line:90%


00:42:23.412 --> 00:42:26.170 align:middle line:84%
So let's try to make
this more precise.

00:42:26.170 --> 00:42:47.410 align:middle line:90%


00:42:47.410 --> 00:42:56.530 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to define two
sequences an and bn.

00:42:56.530 --> 00:43:10.370 align:middle line:84%
So we'll define two
sequences an and bn.

00:43:10.370 --> 00:43:18.930 align:middle line:84%
And an will really
be an, where an

00:43:18.930 --> 00:43:25.480 align:middle line:84%
is going to be bn divided by
10 to the power n minus 1.

00:43:25.480 --> 00:43:28.250 align:middle line:90%


00:43:28.250 --> 00:43:34.410 align:middle line:84%
Remember that anything,
if it's 10 to the power 0,

00:43:34.410 --> 00:43:37.122 align:middle line:90%
by definition, that's 1.

00:43:37.122 --> 00:43:39.060 align:middle line:84%
So this here, in
particular, means

00:43:39.060 --> 00:43:43.130 align:middle line:90%
that a1 should be equal to b1.

00:43:43.130 --> 00:43:48.020 align:middle line:90%


00:43:48.020 --> 00:43:49.800 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to
define it like this.

00:43:49.800 --> 00:43:53.060 align:middle line:90%


00:43:53.060 --> 00:44:00.300 align:middle line:84%
And we are going
to define the bn.

00:44:00.300 --> 00:44:08.540 align:middle line:84%
And the sequences here, so there
will be some properties here,

00:44:08.540 --> 00:44:25.580 align:middle line:84%
that the sequence an
is monotone increasing.

00:44:25.580 --> 00:44:28.740 align:middle line:90%


00:44:28.740 --> 00:44:32.900 align:middle line:84%
an are just real numbers
that is monotone increasing.

00:44:32.900 --> 00:44:37.320 align:middle line:90%


00:44:37.320 --> 00:44:44.130 align:middle line:84%
And the an is going
to be defined.

00:44:44.130 --> 00:44:46.880 align:middle line:90%
And an is defined like that.

00:44:46.880 --> 00:44:53.750 align:middle line:90%


00:44:53.750 --> 00:44:57.910 align:middle line:84%
And the bn are just
natural numbers.

00:44:57.910 --> 00:45:00.940 align:middle line:90%


00:45:00.940 --> 00:45:03.430 align:middle line:90%
So an is defined from bn.

00:45:03.430 --> 00:45:06.210 align:middle line:84%
It's really an that
we are interested in.

00:45:06.210 --> 00:45:08.810 align:middle line:84%
But bn is going to be
a useful tool here.

00:45:08.810 --> 00:45:12.950 align:middle line:90%


00:45:12.950 --> 00:45:14.678 align:middle line:84%
And the bn to some
extent is very simple,

00:45:14.678 --> 00:45:16.220 align:middle line:84%
because they're just
natural numbers.

00:45:16.220 --> 00:45:20.550 align:middle line:90%


00:45:20.550 --> 00:45:25.150 align:middle line:90%
So now we define bn.

00:45:25.150 --> 00:45:55.040 align:middle line:84%
So bn is the largest natural
number such that bn squared is

00:45:55.040 --> 00:46:03.780 align:middle line:84%
lesser or equal to 2 times
10 to the power 2n minus 2.

00:46:03.780 --> 00:46:08.980 align:middle line:90%


00:46:08.980 --> 00:46:13.960 align:middle line:84%
So the sets of natural numbers
that is bounded by that, that's

00:46:13.960 --> 00:46:15.060 align:middle line:90%
like a finite set.

00:46:15.060 --> 00:46:17.200 align:middle line:84%
So you just take the
max or sup or whatever,

00:46:17.200 --> 00:46:18.340 align:middle line:90%
the max of that set.

00:46:18.340 --> 00:46:21.000 align:middle line:90%
It's just the max of that set.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:22.290 align:middle line:90%
So that's a natural number.

00:46:22.290 --> 00:46:29.840 align:middle line:90%


00:46:29.840 --> 00:46:39.170 align:middle line:84%
And now, again, we define,
so now we have the bn's.

00:46:39.170 --> 00:46:40.520 align:middle line:90%
And then again an's.

00:46:40.520 --> 00:46:46.850 align:middle line:90%


00:46:46.850 --> 00:46:53.670 align:middle line:84%
The an are defined to be bn
divided by 10 to the n minus 1.

00:46:53.670 --> 00:47:00.110 align:middle line:90%


00:47:00.110 --> 00:47:02.890 align:middle line:84%
So now the first
thing you observe

00:47:02.890 --> 00:47:10.870 align:middle line:84%
is that if n is equal to 1,
then this thing here is 0.

00:47:10.870 --> 00:47:12.890 align:middle line:90%
So this here is 1.

00:47:12.890 --> 00:47:15.790 align:middle line:84%
So it's the largest
natural number

00:47:15.790 --> 00:47:18.330 align:middle line:84%
so that the square
is less than 2.

00:47:18.330 --> 00:47:25.650 align:middle line:84%
So this means that bn, so n
equal to 1, bn is equal to 1.

00:47:25.650 --> 00:47:30.340 align:middle line:84%
And because this
thing here is also 0,

00:47:30.340 --> 00:47:33.140 align:middle line:90%
so this denominator is 1.

00:47:33.140 --> 00:47:37.980 align:middle line:90%
So a1 is 1.

00:47:37.980 --> 00:47:39.200 align:middle line:90%
b1 is 1.

00:47:39.200 --> 00:47:42.700 align:middle line:90%
And a1 has to be the same as b1.

00:47:42.700 --> 00:47:44.000 align:middle line:90%
And so that's also 1.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:46.606 align:middle line:90%


00:47:46.606 --> 00:47:49.860 align:middle line:90%
So that's how it starts.

00:47:49.860 --> 00:47:57.420 align:middle line:84%
And now we want to prove
that the sequence an is

00:47:57.420 --> 00:47:58.900 align:middle line:90%
monotone increasing.

00:47:58.900 --> 00:48:01.700 align:middle line:84%
We want to prove that an
is monotone increasing.

00:48:01.700 --> 00:48:04.700 align:middle line:84%
So let's just try
to understand that.

00:48:04.700 --> 00:48:07.460 align:middle line:84%
And so again, for
monotone increasing,

00:48:07.460 --> 00:48:10.600 align:middle line:84%
you just need to compare
two consecutive elements.

00:48:10.600 --> 00:48:15.180 align:middle line:90%


00:48:15.180 --> 00:48:20.260 align:middle line:84%
So this here,
remember that there's

00:48:20.260 --> 00:48:23.460 align:middle line:84%
ways to write a formal
proof and then there's

00:48:23.460 --> 00:48:26.680 align:middle line:84%
things you have on the
scrap paper to get the idea.

00:48:26.680 --> 00:48:29.230 align:middle line:84%
So this would be
what we're going on,

00:48:29.230 --> 00:48:32.550 align:middle line:90%
maybe the first statement is.

00:48:32.550 --> 00:48:35.390 align:middle line:84%
You could certainly put
it as part of the proof.

00:48:35.390 --> 00:48:42.930 align:middle line:84%
We want to show that an is less
than or equal to an plus 1.

00:48:42.930 --> 00:48:47.270 align:middle line:90%


00:48:47.270 --> 00:49:03.110 align:middle line:84%
And so this is equivalent
to show that since an here

00:49:03.110 --> 00:49:08.190 align:middle line:84%
is equal to bn divided by
10 to the power n minus 2,

00:49:08.190 --> 00:49:11.590 align:middle line:84%
you want to prove that this
thing here is less than an

00:49:11.590 --> 00:49:23.030 align:middle line:84%
plus 1, which is bn plus 1 over
10 to the n plus 1 minus 1.

00:49:23.030 --> 00:49:31.600 align:middle line:84%
So this here is bn plus
1 over 10 to the power n.

00:49:31.600 --> 00:49:32.940 align:middle line:90%
That's what you want to prove.

00:49:32.940 --> 00:49:37.140 align:middle line:90%


00:49:37.140 --> 00:49:45.160 align:middle line:84%
So you see that we want to show,
this is what we want to prove,

00:49:45.160 --> 00:49:48.000 align:middle line:84%
that this thing here
is less than this.

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:52.920 align:middle line:84%
If you multiply by 10 to
the power n on both sides,

00:49:52.920 --> 00:49:56.560 align:middle line:90%
then you get over here.

00:49:56.560 --> 00:50:02.240 align:middle line:84%
And after you reduce
it, you get 10 bn,

00:50:02.240 --> 00:50:18.040 align:middle line:84%
so you need to show
that 10 bn is less than

00:50:18.040 --> 00:50:22.360 align:middle line:90%
or equal to bn plus 1.

00:50:22.360 --> 00:50:23.970 align:middle line:90%
That's what we need to prove.

00:50:23.970 --> 00:50:27.250 align:middle line:84%
And again, this just
comes from that you

00:50:27.250 --> 00:50:30.370 align:middle line:84%
want to prove-- forget about the
a now-- you can just think about

00:50:30.370 --> 00:50:34.210 align:middle line:84%
that we need to prove that this
thing here is less than this.

00:50:34.210 --> 00:50:37.970 align:middle line:84%
Multiply over by 10 to
the n on both sides,

00:50:37.970 --> 00:50:40.590 align:middle line:84%
then there's still
10 times bn left.

00:50:40.590 --> 00:50:44.110 align:middle line:90%
And here it's just bn plus 1.

00:50:44.110 --> 00:50:46.950 align:middle line:84%
So we need to show
this one here.

00:50:46.950 --> 00:50:49.990 align:middle line:84%
And so if I was
to write it down,

00:50:49.990 --> 00:50:53.370 align:middle line:84%
I would probably have some
of this on scrap paper.

00:50:53.370 --> 00:50:56.210 align:middle line:84%
And then I would instead
establish this here

00:50:56.210 --> 00:50:59.450 align:middle line:84%
first, and then say, therefore,
and then I'll conclude why.

00:50:59.450 --> 00:51:02.170 align:middle line:90%


00:51:02.170 --> 00:51:05.230 align:middle line:84%
But of course, that's not the
way you're thinking about it.

00:51:05.230 --> 00:51:08.730 align:middle line:84%
You first try to analyze
what you have to prove.

00:51:08.730 --> 00:51:11.130 align:middle line:84%
And then once you
know that, then you

00:51:11.130 --> 00:51:12.400 align:middle line:90%
try to write it down nicely.

00:51:12.400 --> 00:51:14.910 align:middle line:90%


00:51:14.910 --> 00:51:16.830 align:middle line:90%
So we need to prove this here.

00:51:16.830 --> 00:51:22.180 align:middle line:90%


00:51:22.180 --> 00:51:30.260 align:middle line:84%
So now the thing is that
we have that the definition

00:51:30.260 --> 00:51:34.120 align:middle line:84%
of bn, which is right here,
that's the definition of bn.

00:51:34.120 --> 00:51:36.500 align:middle line:90%
But let me copy it over here.

00:51:36.500 --> 00:51:40.220 align:middle line:84%
So we know that bn squared
is less than or equal to,

00:51:40.220 --> 00:51:43.820 align:middle line:84%
it's the largest integer so
that you have this thing here.

00:51:43.820 --> 00:51:47.780 align:middle line:90%


00:51:47.780 --> 00:51:50.980 align:middle line:84%
But this means that if
you're looking at 10 bn,

00:51:50.980 --> 00:51:52.860 align:middle line:90%
that's still an integer.

00:51:52.860 --> 00:51:56.060 align:middle line:84%
And if you square
this here, then this

00:51:56.060 --> 00:52:02.020 align:middle line:84%
is the same as 100
times bn squared.

00:52:02.020 --> 00:52:06.970 align:middle line:84%
And so that actually has to
be less than 100 times this.

00:52:06.970 --> 00:52:10.140 align:middle line:90%


00:52:10.140 --> 00:52:15.480 align:middle line:84%
So it just becomes less than
or equal to 2 10 to the 2n,

00:52:15.480 --> 00:52:17.100 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:52:17.100 --> 00:52:24.550 align:middle line:84%
And this here you can also
write as 2 to the 10 times 10

00:52:24.550 --> 00:52:30.110 align:middle line:90%
to the power 2n plus 1 minus 2.

00:52:30.110 --> 00:52:36.710 align:middle line:84%
But now, you see that bn,
so 10 bn is an integer

00:52:36.710 --> 00:52:38.550 align:middle line:90%
and it has this property.

00:52:38.550 --> 00:52:43.870 align:middle line:84%
But bn plus 1 was supposed to
be the largest integer so that

00:52:43.870 --> 00:52:52.870 align:middle line:84%
the square here is less than 2
times 10 to 2n plus 1 minus 2.

00:52:52.870 --> 00:52:59.390 align:middle line:84%
So you see that bn plus 1 is the
largest one with this property.

00:52:59.390 --> 00:53:11.190 align:middle line:84%
So you conclude that since
bn plus 1 is the largest

00:53:11.190 --> 00:53:18.120 align:middle line:84%
and both are integers,
and bn is an integer,

00:53:18.120 --> 00:53:26.280 align:middle line:84%
then bn plus 1 must be
bigger or equal to bn--

00:53:26.280 --> 00:53:29.345 align:middle line:84%
must be bigger than
10 times bn, right?

00:53:29.345 --> 00:53:32.960 align:middle line:90%


00:53:32.960 --> 00:53:35.732 align:middle line:84%
And that's exactly what
we wanted to prove,

00:53:35.732 --> 00:53:40.320 align:middle line:84%
that the bn plus 1
was bigger than bn.

00:53:40.320 --> 00:53:43.520 align:middle line:84%
So we now have that
the sequence an

00:53:43.520 --> 00:53:46.320 align:middle line:84%
defined this slightly
cryptical way,

00:53:46.320 --> 00:53:50.280 align:middle line:84%
but really, it sounds
maybe cryptical,

00:53:50.280 --> 00:53:57.260 align:middle line:84%
but it's just instead of
using somehow digital numbers,

00:53:57.260 --> 00:54:02.360 align:middle line:84%
you're just thinking about
you want this and that many--

00:54:02.360 --> 00:54:06.680 align:middle line:84%
the n is referring to
the number of digits,

00:54:06.680 --> 00:54:12.360 align:middle line:84%
but including the digits
that is before the point.

00:54:12.360 --> 00:54:14.460 align:middle line:84%
So it's actually
not very cryptical,

00:54:14.460 --> 00:54:17.290 align:middle line:84%
but it maybe sounds
a little formal here.

00:54:17.290 --> 00:54:23.890 align:middle line:84%
OK, so we have an is
an increasing sequence.

00:54:23.890 --> 00:54:25.950 align:middle line:90%
Now, why is an bounded?

00:54:25.950 --> 00:54:28.890 align:middle line:90%


00:54:28.890 --> 00:54:33.570 align:middle line:84%
But the an is
defined from the bn.

00:54:33.570 --> 00:54:38.370 align:middle line:84%
So in order to show
that an is bounded,

00:54:38.370 --> 00:54:42.210 align:middle line:84%
you have to figure out
what is a bound for the bn.

00:54:42.210 --> 00:54:48.830 align:middle line:84%
But you have this here, bn
is the largest such number.

00:54:48.830 --> 00:54:53.530 align:middle line:84%
If I take 2 times 10
to the power n minus 1,

00:54:53.530 --> 00:54:57.610 align:middle line:84%
suppose I take this number
here and I square it.

00:54:57.610 --> 00:54:59.610 align:middle line:90%
This is definitely an integer.

00:54:59.610 --> 00:55:01.010 align:middle line:90%
I square it.

00:55:01.010 --> 00:55:06.290 align:middle line:84%
Then I'm getting 4 times
10 to the power 2n minus 2.

00:55:06.290 --> 00:55:10.810 align:middle line:84%
So this in here, this here
is the same as over here.

00:55:10.810 --> 00:55:12.570 align:middle line:90%
But it's now 4.

00:55:12.570 --> 00:55:16.880 align:middle line:84%
So this number here would
not be allowed as a bn.

00:55:16.880 --> 00:55:20.120 align:middle line:84%
In fact, it would
be larger than bn.

00:55:20.120 --> 00:55:26.360 align:middle line:84%
So bn is less than 2 to the
power, 10 to the n minus 1.

00:55:26.360 --> 00:55:30.415 align:middle line:90%


00:55:30.415 --> 00:55:39.140 align:middle line:84%
So this means that an, which is
equal to bn over 10 to the power

00:55:39.140 --> 00:55:44.180 align:middle line:84%
n minus 1, but this is now, you
see, less than or equal to 2.

00:55:44.180 --> 00:55:47.060 align:middle line:90%


00:55:47.060 --> 00:55:50.700 align:middle line:84%
So the sequence an
that we have defined

00:55:50.700 --> 00:55:54.860 align:middle line:84%
is, as you would
have expected, they

00:55:54.860 --> 00:55:58.680 align:middle line:84%
are increasing because,
if you think about it,

00:55:58.680 --> 00:56:03.620 align:middle line:84%
it's really defined to
take the number of digits,

00:56:03.620 --> 00:56:06.760 align:middle line:84%
it's going to be like the number
of digits in square root of 2,

00:56:06.760 --> 00:56:09.640 align:middle line:90%
including the 1, the starting 1.

00:56:09.640 --> 00:56:16.110 align:middle line:90%


00:56:16.110 --> 00:56:18.470 align:middle line:84%
So they all are going
to be less than 2.

00:56:18.470 --> 00:56:56.590 align:middle line:90%


00:56:56.590 --> 00:57:00.910 align:middle line:84%
So we have that an is
an increasing sequence

00:57:00.910 --> 00:57:01.740 align:middle line:90%
and is bounded.

00:57:01.740 --> 00:57:04.670 align:middle line:90%


00:57:04.670 --> 00:57:21.320 align:middle line:84%
So an, here, is convergent
by the monotone convergence

00:57:21.320 --> 00:57:21.820 align:middle line:90%
theorem.

00:57:21.820 --> 00:57:28.946 align:middle line:90%


00:57:28.946 --> 00:57:34.440 align:middle line:84%
So the an is convergent by the
monotone convergence theorem.

00:57:34.440 --> 00:57:40.000 align:middle line:84%
But now, if I'm looking
at an squared, an squared,

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:44.440 align:middle line:84%
well, an squared is the
same as an times an.

00:57:44.440 --> 00:57:51.720 align:middle line:90%


00:57:51.720 --> 00:58:01.160 align:middle line:84%
But an, by definition,
was bn divided by 10

00:58:01.160 --> 00:58:06.640 align:middle line:90%
to the power n minus 1.

00:58:06.640 --> 00:58:13.170 align:middle line:84%
And so I can write it like
this, 10 to the power n minus 1.

00:58:13.170 --> 00:58:16.370 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that you can
write this as bn squared.

00:58:16.370 --> 00:58:21.370 align:middle line:84%
And then these are
combined to 2n minus 2.

00:58:21.370 --> 00:58:26.090 align:middle line:84%
And by assumption, if
you divide by this here,

00:58:26.090 --> 00:58:28.710 align:middle line:84%
this thing here is less
than or equal to 2.

00:58:28.710 --> 00:58:34.410 align:middle line:90%


00:58:34.410 --> 00:58:38.633 align:middle line:84%
So you have that
an converges to a.

00:58:38.633 --> 00:58:40.050 align:middle line:84%
And if you want
to think about it,

00:58:40.050 --> 00:58:43.410 align:middle line:84%
you think about
this sequence again.

00:58:43.410 --> 00:58:49.970 align:middle line:84%
And so now you know that an, by
the product rule for sequences,

00:58:49.970 --> 00:58:53.330 align:middle line:84%
an times an, the
sequence times itself,

00:58:53.330 --> 00:58:57.850 align:middle line:90%
is converging to a squared.

00:58:57.850 --> 00:59:03.250 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here, because
each of these squares

00:59:03.250 --> 00:59:06.820 align:middle line:84%
here, each of them is
less than or equal to 2,

00:59:06.820 --> 00:59:09.080 align:middle line:84%
then the limit must be
less than or equal to 2.

00:59:09.080 --> 00:59:14.780 align:middle line:90%


00:59:14.780 --> 00:59:19.440 align:middle line:84%
What I want to prove now is that
this a that we get as a limit,

00:59:19.440 --> 00:59:22.940 align:middle line:84%
that the square is,
in fact, equal to 2.

00:59:22.940 --> 00:59:33.020 align:middle line:84%
I want to show that the
square, when we're doing it,

00:59:33.020 --> 00:59:36.100 align:middle line:84%
this is one more proof
that square root of 2

00:59:36.100 --> 00:59:37.000 align:middle line:90%
is a real number.

00:59:37.000 --> 00:59:39.420 align:middle line:84%
But this is in a way
how you think about it,

00:59:39.420 --> 00:59:44.328 align:middle line:90%
in terms of the decimals.

00:59:44.328 --> 00:59:48.500 align:middle line:84%
And so we have this sequence
an, and we have proven

00:59:48.500 --> 00:59:50.720 align:middle line:90%
that it's converging to some a.

00:59:50.720 --> 00:59:56.260 align:middle line:84%
And we've shown that this a here
has a property that a squared is

00:59:56.260 --> 00:59:59.640 align:middle line:90%
less than or equal to 2.

00:59:59.640 --> 01:00:14.950 align:middle line:84%
So I want to show that a
squared is actually equal to 2.

01:00:14.950 --> 01:00:17.310 align:middle line:90%
That's what I want to prove.

01:00:17.310 --> 01:00:19.430 align:middle line:84%
But I've already
proven that a squared

01:00:19.430 --> 01:00:23.755 align:middle line:84%
is less than or
equal to 2, so enough

01:00:23.755 --> 01:00:29.050 align:middle line:84%
to show that a squared
is bigger or equal to 2.

01:00:29.050 --> 01:00:32.010 align:middle line:90%


01:00:32.010 --> 01:00:33.370 align:middle line:90%
So let's try to do that.

01:00:33.370 --> 01:00:39.230 align:middle line:90%


01:00:39.230 --> 01:00:41.670 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to
use, this is going

01:00:41.670 --> 01:00:46.190 align:middle line:84%
to be another illustration
of the algebraic rules

01:00:46.190 --> 01:00:48.210 align:middle line:90%
for sequences.

01:00:48.210 --> 01:00:55.710 align:middle line:90%


01:00:55.710 --> 01:01:00.190 align:middle line:84%
Here, now, really to prove that
is less than or equal to 2,

01:01:00.190 --> 01:01:05.920 align:middle line:84%
I didn't use fully the
definition of the an

01:01:05.920 --> 01:01:12.360 align:middle line:84%
because I didn't really use that
it was the largest such that an

01:01:12.360 --> 01:01:21.960 align:middle line:84%
was defined in terms of bn,
where bn was the largest

01:01:21.960 --> 01:01:22.630 align:middle line:90%
such number.

01:01:22.630 --> 01:01:28.280 align:middle line:90%


01:01:28.280 --> 01:01:34.000 align:middle line:84%
Suppose now I'm looking
at bn and I'm adding 1

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:35.260 align:middle line:90%
and I'm squaring it.

01:01:35.260 --> 01:01:37.808 align:middle line:90%


01:01:37.808 --> 01:01:43.520 align:middle line:84%
Well, this here cannot also
be smaller than this here,

01:01:43.520 --> 01:01:50.280 align:middle line:84%
because then the bn should
have been this in here.

01:01:50.280 --> 01:01:54.760 align:middle line:84%
So this here must actually
be strictly larger than 2 10

01:01:54.760 --> 01:01:56.580 align:middle line:90%
to the power 2n minus 2.

01:01:56.580 --> 01:02:00.180 align:middle line:90%


01:02:00.180 --> 01:02:06.810 align:middle line:84%
And so now you just divide
by this on both sides.

01:02:06.810 --> 01:02:12.270 align:middle line:90%
So you have bn plus 1 squared.

01:02:12.270 --> 01:02:16.870 align:middle line:84%
And you divide it by 10
to the power 2n minus 2.

01:02:16.870 --> 01:02:19.030 align:middle line:84%
So you know that this
thing is bigger than 2.

01:02:19.030 --> 01:02:21.690 align:middle line:90%


01:02:21.690 --> 01:02:24.770 align:middle line:84%
But you can write this in
here, this denominator,

01:02:24.770 --> 01:02:29.690 align:middle line:84%
10 to the power 2n minus 2, you
can write as 10 to the power n

01:02:29.690 --> 01:02:34.090 align:middle line:84%
minus 1 times 10 to
the power n minus 1.

01:02:34.090 --> 01:02:36.430 align:middle line:84%
So in this way, you
can split this up.

01:02:36.430 --> 01:02:42.850 align:middle line:84%
And you can write it
as bn plus 1 over 10

01:02:42.850 --> 01:02:47.920 align:middle line:84%
to the power n minus 1,
and then times itself.

01:02:47.920 --> 01:02:50.570 align:middle line:90%


01:02:50.570 --> 01:02:57.850 align:middle line:84%
This is just to make sure that
it's bn, and then to the bn

01:02:57.850 --> 01:03:01.140 align:middle line:90%
you're adding 1.

01:03:01.140 --> 01:03:06.780 align:middle line:84%
So like that, you
write it like that.

01:03:06.780 --> 01:03:16.140 align:middle line:84%
But you see, this thing here,
if you split the fraction up,

01:03:16.140 --> 01:03:23.340 align:middle line:84%
you can write it as bn over
10 to the power n minus 1.

01:03:23.340 --> 01:03:28.220 align:middle line:84%
And then you can add 1 over
10 to the power n minus 1.

01:03:28.220 --> 01:03:31.580 align:middle line:84%
And then you can
multiply that by 2.

01:03:31.580 --> 01:03:33.040 align:middle line:90%
And you can write it like that.

01:03:33.040 --> 01:03:41.220 align:middle line:90%


01:03:41.220 --> 01:03:47.020 align:middle line:84%
But now you see, now I
can write this thing here.

01:03:47.020 --> 01:03:50.980 align:middle line:90%


01:03:50.980 --> 01:03:55.920 align:middle line:84%
Now I can think about it in
a slightly different way.

01:03:55.920 --> 01:03:58.030 align:middle line:90%
So I can write this thing here.

01:03:58.030 --> 01:04:02.000 align:middle line:84%
This thing here, that
is the definition of an.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:07.030 align:middle line:90%


01:04:07.030 --> 01:04:13.270 align:middle line:84%
So what I have here is
that an plus 1 over 10

01:04:13.270 --> 01:04:17.130 align:middle line:84%
to the power n minus
1 times itself,

01:04:17.130 --> 01:04:19.590 align:middle line:84%
but I will just
write it nicely out

01:04:19.590 --> 01:04:26.730 align:middle line:84%
like this, that this thing
here, remember the way it goes,

01:04:26.730 --> 01:04:30.070 align:middle line:84%
that this is equal to that
which is bigger than 2,

01:04:30.070 --> 01:04:31.690 align:middle line:90%
so this is bigger than 2.

01:04:31.690 --> 01:04:35.430 align:middle line:90%


01:04:35.430 --> 01:04:41.430 align:middle line:84%
Now, 1 over 10 to the n, you can
think about that as a sequence.

01:04:41.430 --> 01:04:43.250 align:middle line:84%
You can think about
this as a sequence.

01:04:43.250 --> 01:04:45.230 align:middle line:90%
That sequence goes to 0.

01:04:45.230 --> 01:04:47.002 align:middle line:90%
This here goes to a.

01:04:47.002 --> 01:04:50.990 align:middle line:84%
The sum of these two sequences,
by the algebraic rules,

01:04:50.990 --> 01:04:53.190 align:middle line:90%
go to the sum of the limits.

01:04:53.190 --> 01:04:55.730 align:middle line:84%
So this is a plus
0, so that's a.

01:04:55.730 --> 01:04:58.790 align:middle line:90%
So this thing here goes to a.

01:04:58.790 --> 01:05:02.040 align:middle line:84%
And this is the same,
so this goes to a.

01:05:02.040 --> 01:05:07.720 align:middle line:84%
So you see that by the
product rule for the limit,

01:05:07.720 --> 01:05:12.520 align:middle line:84%
the limit here is, so you
get that a squared here.

01:05:12.520 --> 01:05:14.560 align:middle line:84%
And since it holds
for each element,

01:05:14.560 --> 01:05:17.320 align:middle line:84%
then it also holds
for the limit.

01:05:17.320 --> 01:05:19.520 align:middle line:84%
Except you have to be
a little bit careful--

01:05:19.520 --> 01:05:24.440 align:middle line:84%
it may not be strict inequality,
but just big or equal to.

01:05:24.440 --> 01:05:29.120 align:middle line:84%
And of course, in fact, it
is equal to because now you

01:05:29.120 --> 01:05:32.640 align:middle line:84%
have established the other
inequality that a squared was

01:05:32.640 --> 01:05:34.640 align:middle line:90%
bigger or equal to 2.

01:05:34.640 --> 01:05:37.180 align:middle line:84%
We had already proven that
a squared was less than

01:05:37.180 --> 01:05:38.360 align:middle line:90%
or equal to 2.

01:05:38.360 --> 01:05:42.440 align:middle line:84%
So you conclude that a
squared is equal to 2.

01:05:42.440 --> 01:05:47.080 align:middle line:84%
If you just think about it,
it sounds maybe a little

01:05:47.080 --> 01:05:48.560 align:middle line:90%
bit convoluted.

01:05:48.560 --> 01:05:52.040 align:middle line:84%
But it's really writing
down precisely what

01:05:52.040 --> 01:05:53.930 align:middle line:84%
you think about
when you're thinking

01:05:53.930 --> 01:05:56.970 align:middle line:84%
about a square root of 2
because you're thinking

01:05:56.970 --> 01:05:58.510 align:middle line:90%
about the number of digits.

01:05:58.510 --> 01:06:04.510 align:middle line:84%
And so including the
first, the 1 in 1.4,

01:06:04.510 --> 01:06:07.410 align:middle line:84%
blah, blah, blah,
including that 1,

01:06:07.410 --> 01:06:12.090 align:middle line:84%
if you think about the number
of digits, like the an,

01:06:12.090 --> 01:06:16.850 align:middle line:84%
then the an is really
defined to make it precise.

01:06:16.850 --> 01:06:19.730 align:middle line:84%
You would define it in terms
of this other sequence bn.

01:06:19.730 --> 01:06:25.970 align:middle line:90%


01:06:25.970 --> 01:06:30.330 align:middle line:84%
So this was just a
little illustration

01:06:30.330 --> 01:06:32.920 align:middle line:84%
of how the monotone
convergence theorem works.

01:06:32.920 --> 01:06:36.298 align:middle line:90%


01:06:36.298 --> 01:06:41.610 align:middle line:84%
And this will play an
important role next time.

01:06:41.610 --> 01:06:42.650 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:06:42.650 --> 01:06:45.650 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So the
reason why at the top

01:06:45.650 --> 01:06:48.030 align:middle line:84%
we have strictly greater than
2, and then at the bottom,

01:06:48.030 --> 01:06:50.730 align:middle line:84%
we have greater or equal
to 2 is because the a's

01:06:50.730 --> 01:06:53.380 align:middle line:84%
and the a squared are
limits, whereas on the top,

01:06:53.380 --> 01:06:56.260 align:middle line:84%
we're considering each
element in the sequence?

01:06:56.260 --> 01:06:59.417 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: So
this here, the an,

01:06:59.417 --> 01:07:01.000 align:middle line:84%
you're talking about
this here, right?

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:01.860 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:07:01.860 --> 01:07:03.995 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: So
the an converges to a.

01:07:03.995 --> 01:07:04.620 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:07:04.620 --> 01:07:06.340 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Right?

01:07:06.340 --> 01:07:09.060 align:middle line:84%
I think about this here,
so I think about a sequence

01:07:09.060 --> 01:07:11.280 align:middle line:90%
plus another sequence.

01:07:11.280 --> 01:07:14.180 align:middle line:84%
This sequence here
converges to 0.

01:07:14.180 --> 01:07:16.500 align:middle line:84%
So the sum of
these two sequences

01:07:16.500 --> 01:07:19.400 align:middle line:84%
converges to 0, and
likewise for this.

01:07:19.400 --> 01:07:23.660 align:middle line:84%
And then I'm thinking about it
as a product of this sequence

01:07:23.660 --> 01:07:26.260 align:middle line:90%
with that sequence.

01:07:26.260 --> 01:07:31.700 align:middle line:84%
But it's like each element
in the product sequence

01:07:31.700 --> 01:07:33.780 align:middle line:90%
is strictly bigger than 2.

01:07:33.780 --> 01:07:37.320 align:middle line:84%
But it doesn't necessarily mean
that the limit is strictly.

01:07:37.320 --> 01:07:40.140 align:middle line:84%
But the limit has to be
bigger than 2 because they

01:07:40.140 --> 01:07:41.640 align:middle line:90%
could kind of approach 2.

01:07:41.640 --> 01:07:43.480 align:middle line:84%
And that's exactly what
happened, of course.

01:07:43.480 --> 01:07:46.940 align:middle line:90%


01:07:46.940 --> 01:07:51.390 align:middle line:84%
So I also just want to say
that this limsup and liminf--

01:07:51.390 --> 01:07:53.790 align:middle line:84%
well, we didn't
actually define it.

01:07:53.790 --> 01:07:58.110 align:middle line:84%
And it is how you
define it usually.

01:07:58.110 --> 01:08:00.670 align:middle line:84%
But we haven't talked
about that concept yet.

01:08:00.670 --> 01:08:03.330 align:middle line:84%
But this, I talked
about with that,

01:08:03.330 --> 01:08:05.190 align:middle line:84%
if you take a bounded
sequence, then

01:08:05.190 --> 01:08:08.270 align:middle line:84%
you could form two
monotone sequences.

01:08:08.270 --> 01:08:10.550 align:middle line:84%
This will play a
really important role

01:08:10.550 --> 01:08:11.990 align:middle line:90%
for several things.

01:08:11.990 --> 01:08:15.230 align:middle line:84%
This is how one defines
limsup and liminf.

01:08:15.230 --> 01:08:17.109 align:middle line:84%
We haven't talked
about those yet.

01:08:17.109 --> 01:08:22.930 align:middle line:84%
It's also going to be used to
prove an important theorem,

01:08:22.930 --> 01:08:24.229 align:middle line:90%
really important theorem.

01:08:24.229 --> 01:08:27.649 align:middle line:84%
And I will talk about
that theorem next.

01:08:27.649 --> 01:08:30.430 align:middle line:84%
But we won't prove
it before next time.

01:08:30.430 --> 01:08:35.270 align:middle line:84%
So what is that stuff
going to be used for?

01:08:35.270 --> 01:08:41.262 align:middle line:84%
And the monotone, what
is another application?

01:08:41.262 --> 01:08:43.470 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, there will be
several other applications

01:08:43.470 --> 01:08:44.940 align:middle line:90%
of monotone convergence theorem.

01:08:44.940 --> 01:08:49.279 align:middle line:90%


01:08:49.279 --> 01:08:52.080 align:middle line:84%
Here's a really
important concept.

01:08:52.080 --> 01:08:56.772 align:middle line:90%
And so sometimes it's hard.

01:08:56.772 --> 01:08:59.200 align:middle line:84%
If it was a monotone
sequence, then

01:08:59.200 --> 01:09:02.899 align:middle line:84%
you could write down
explicitly what the limit was.

01:09:02.899 --> 01:09:06.600 align:middle line:84%
And in all of the
examples we saw so far,

01:09:06.600 --> 01:09:09.460 align:middle line:84%
it was easy to write
down the limits.

01:09:09.460 --> 01:09:13.660 align:middle line:84%
But in general, you might not
be able to write down the limit,

01:09:13.660 --> 01:09:16.200 align:middle line:84%
but you want to prove
that the limit exists.

01:09:16.200 --> 01:09:18.960 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
following notion

01:09:18.960 --> 01:09:21.240 align:middle line:90%
that then becomes really handy.

01:09:21.240 --> 01:09:23.130 align:middle line:84%
And that's the notion
of a Cauchy sequence.

01:09:23.130 --> 01:09:28.840 align:middle line:90%


01:09:28.840 --> 01:09:31.000 align:middle line:90%
So what is a Cauchy sequence?

01:09:31.000 --> 01:09:45.120 align:middle line:84%
So a Cauchy sequence, it's
a sequence with the property

01:09:45.120 --> 01:09:54.410 align:middle line:84%
that for all epsilon
greater than 0,

01:09:54.410 --> 01:10:03.702 align:middle line:84%
there exists N, just
a natural number N,

01:10:03.702 --> 01:10:11.850 align:middle line:84%
such that if n and m are bigger
than this natural number, then

01:10:11.850 --> 01:10:19.220 align:middle line:84%
the two elements an and am
are less than epsilon apart.

01:10:19.220 --> 01:10:24.050 align:middle line:90%


01:10:24.050 --> 01:10:26.910 align:middle line:84%
So this is a different
notion than convergence.

01:10:26.910 --> 01:10:32.370 align:middle line:84%
Convergence says that a
sequence is convergent

01:10:32.370 --> 01:10:36.980 align:middle line:84%
if everything kind of far out
accumulates around the limit.

01:10:36.980 --> 01:10:44.500 align:middle line:90%


01:10:44.500 --> 01:10:50.540 align:middle line:84%
So this here says that a Cauchy
sequence, that's a sequence so

01:10:50.540 --> 01:10:54.700 align:middle line:84%
that if you're far out,
then things bunch together,

01:10:54.700 --> 01:10:56.060 align:middle line:90%
basically.

01:10:56.060 --> 01:10:58.580 align:middle line:90%
Now, of course, we will prove.

01:10:58.580 --> 01:11:07.890 align:middle line:84%
And so we will prove on R. We
will prove the Cauchy sequence.

01:11:07.890 --> 01:11:16.380 align:middle line:90%


01:11:16.380 --> 01:11:18.330 align:middle line:90%
So we'll prove the following.

01:11:18.330 --> 01:11:21.525 align:middle line:90%


01:11:21.525 --> 01:11:22.800 align:middle line:90%
Prove the following theorem--

01:11:22.800 --> 01:11:26.460 align:middle line:90%


01:11:26.460 --> 01:11:28.600 align:middle line:84%
for now, everything is
in R at the moment--

01:11:28.600 --> 01:11:31.660 align:middle line:90%


01:11:31.660 --> 01:11:48.312 align:middle line:84%
that a sequence is
a Cauchy sequence

01:11:48.312 --> 01:11:53.330 align:middle line:90%
if and only if it is convergent.

01:11:53.330 --> 01:11:56.630 align:middle line:90%


01:11:56.630 --> 01:12:01.030 align:middle line:84%
I won't prove this now, but
I'll prove this next time.

01:12:01.030 --> 01:12:05.550 align:middle line:84%
And again, the proof of
this involved this stuff

01:12:05.550 --> 01:12:08.030 align:middle line:84%
where we defined
these two sequences

01:12:08.030 --> 01:12:09.610 align:middle line:90%
from that bounded sequence.

01:12:09.610 --> 01:12:12.130 align:middle line:90%
So it would be useful there.

01:12:12.130 --> 01:12:15.630 align:middle line:90%


01:12:15.630 --> 01:12:18.260 align:middle line:84%
Now, let me give
you some examples.

01:12:18.260 --> 01:12:25.150 align:middle line:90%


01:12:25.150 --> 01:12:33.350 align:middle line:84%
One example, and we'll get to
that later, but at the moment,

01:12:33.350 --> 01:12:36.590 align:middle line:84%
we talk, everything
is in R. And then we

01:12:36.590 --> 01:12:38.530 align:middle line:90%
will later generalize this.

01:12:38.530 --> 01:12:42.960 align:middle line:84%
And so to generalize this,
a lot of these concepts

01:12:42.960 --> 01:12:45.320 align:middle line:90%
work much more general.

01:12:45.320 --> 01:12:49.052 align:middle line:90%
And that's extremely useful.

01:12:49.052 --> 01:12:53.600 align:middle line:84%
And it can be used
to find solutions

01:12:53.600 --> 01:12:56.600 align:middle line:90%
to differential equations.

01:12:56.600 --> 01:13:01.080 align:middle line:84%
But then you have to
abstract these concepts

01:13:01.080 --> 01:13:04.200 align:middle line:84%
to where sequences are
not any more real numbers,

01:13:04.200 --> 01:13:06.140 align:middle line:84%
but they are of
some other space.

01:13:06.140 --> 01:13:09.320 align:middle line:84%
And then you have to talk
about convergence, et cetera.

01:13:09.320 --> 01:13:13.040 align:middle line:84%
And so you can
use this to define

01:13:13.040 --> 01:13:18.440 align:middle line:84%
solutions to show that various
differential equations have

01:13:18.440 --> 01:13:20.286 align:middle line:90%
solutions.

01:13:20.286 --> 01:13:23.640 align:middle line:84%
And so that often
goes over using

01:13:23.640 --> 01:13:25.610 align:middle line:84%
what's called the
contracting mapping theorem.

01:13:25.610 --> 01:13:33.263 align:middle line:90%


01:13:33.263 --> 01:13:33.930 align:middle line:90%
Mapping theorem.

01:13:33.930 --> 01:13:39.850 align:middle line:90%


01:13:39.850 --> 01:13:44.290 align:middle line:84%
And the contraction mapping
theorem have all kinds of forms.

01:13:44.290 --> 01:13:46.810 align:middle line:90%


01:13:46.810 --> 01:13:51.410 align:middle line:84%
But they're all, it's just
a matter of what space

01:13:51.410 --> 01:13:54.530 align:middle line:90%
you're looking at, and so on.

01:13:54.530 --> 01:13:57.350 align:middle line:84%
So we're looking at
R here in this case.

01:13:57.350 --> 01:13:59.490 align:middle line:84%
And so the contracting
mapping theorem,

01:13:59.490 --> 01:14:05.850 align:middle line:84%
so a map is just a
map here from R to R.

01:14:05.850 --> 01:14:09.730 align:middle line:84%
And that the map is
contracting means that if you

01:14:09.730 --> 01:14:14.190 align:middle line:90%
take two elements in R--

01:14:14.190 --> 01:14:17.290 align:middle line:90%


01:14:17.290 --> 01:14:22.780 align:middle line:90%
sorry, T is a contracting map.

01:14:22.780 --> 01:14:35.610 align:middle line:90%


01:14:35.610 --> 01:14:38.832 align:middle line:84%
And this is really
important-- c is positive.

01:14:38.832 --> 01:14:40.040 align:middle line:90%
I mean, that's not important.

01:14:40.040 --> 01:14:41.920 align:middle line:90%
It had to be positive.

01:14:41.920 --> 01:14:45.460 align:middle line:84%
But the important
point is that c

01:14:45.460 --> 01:14:47.320 align:middle line:90%
has to be strictly less than 1.

01:14:47.320 --> 01:14:50.980 align:middle line:90%
That's a crucial point.

01:14:50.980 --> 01:15:00.460 align:middle line:84%
And then it has a property
that when you take x and y in R

01:15:00.460 --> 01:15:05.400 align:middle line:84%
and you're looking at how
close x and y are together,

01:15:05.400 --> 01:15:14.540 align:middle line:84%
so how close that the image
under T of x and y, how close

01:15:14.540 --> 01:15:19.240 align:middle line:84%
they are together, then
those have to be some factor.

01:15:19.240 --> 01:15:21.990 align:middle line:84%
And this is the factor,
the c is the factor.

01:15:21.990 --> 01:15:25.760 align:middle line:90%


01:15:25.760 --> 01:15:27.720 align:middle line:90%
So they have to come closer.

01:15:27.720 --> 01:15:30.560 align:middle line:84%
This is why c has to
be strictly less than 1

01:15:30.560 --> 01:15:32.320 align:middle line:84%
because they have
to come closer,

01:15:32.320 --> 01:15:36.670 align:middle line:84%
if they come closer by a factor
than the original one was.

01:15:36.670 --> 01:15:40.370 align:middle line:90%


01:15:40.370 --> 01:15:43.670 align:middle line:90%
So this is a contracting map.

01:15:43.670 --> 01:15:47.430 align:middle line:84%
So a contracting
map is a map from R

01:15:47.430 --> 01:15:52.790 align:middle line:84%
to R so that there exists some
constant strictly less than 1,

01:15:52.790 --> 01:15:55.590 align:middle line:84%
so that for all
x and y, you have

01:15:55.590 --> 01:15:58.870 align:middle line:84%
that the difference
between the images

01:15:58.870 --> 01:16:02.590 align:middle line:84%
is this factor that is
strictly less than 1

01:16:02.590 --> 01:16:05.190 align:middle line:90%
with what they were originally.

01:16:05.190 --> 01:16:07.770 align:middle line:84%
And so now you get the
contracting mapping theorem.

01:16:07.770 --> 01:16:09.710 align:middle line:84%
And we'll talk about
the proof next time.

01:16:09.710 --> 01:16:16.550 align:middle line:84%
And again, once you know
the more abstract concepts,

01:16:16.550 --> 01:16:18.470 align:middle line:90%
then it's quite easy.

01:16:18.470 --> 01:16:21.230 align:middle line:84%
The proof is going to be the
same, et cetera, et cetera.

01:16:21.230 --> 01:16:23.470 align:middle line:84%
And it will give you
existence of solutions

01:16:23.470 --> 01:16:25.510 align:middle line:84%
to a lot of
differential equation.

01:16:25.510 --> 01:16:27.420 align:middle line:84%
So this is the contracting
mapping theorem.

01:16:27.420 --> 01:16:37.520 align:middle line:90%


01:16:37.520 --> 01:16:47.440 align:middle line:84%
So it's saying the following,
that if T from R to R

01:16:47.440 --> 01:17:04.350 align:middle line:84%
is a contracting map,
then T has a fixed point.

01:17:04.350 --> 01:17:08.260 align:middle line:90%


01:17:08.260 --> 01:17:09.690 align:middle line:90%
It has a fixed point.

01:17:09.690 --> 01:17:13.720 align:middle line:90%


01:17:13.720 --> 01:17:19.160 align:middle line:84%
And this means that
T of x is equal to x.

01:17:19.160 --> 01:17:23.080 align:middle line:84%
And when you apply
this theorem, so this

01:17:23.080 --> 01:17:27.280 align:middle line:84%
is the contracting mapping,
and again it's crucial

01:17:27.280 --> 01:17:30.140 align:middle line:90%
that this c is less than 1.

01:17:30.140 --> 01:17:32.370 align:middle line:90%
That's what makes everything go.

01:17:32.370 --> 01:17:35.930 align:middle line:84%
If it was equal to 1, you
wouldn't get anything.

01:17:35.930 --> 01:17:38.650 align:middle line:84%
It has to be
strictly less than 1.

01:17:38.650 --> 01:17:42.890 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here, if you
set it up more generally,

01:17:42.890 --> 01:17:47.330 align:middle line:84%
if the spaces are more general
than just the real numbers,

01:17:47.330 --> 01:17:51.730 align:middle line:84%
then this here will be
that you have a solution--

01:17:51.730 --> 01:17:53.590 align:middle line:84%
it could be applied
to many other things--

01:17:53.590 --> 01:17:56.970 align:middle line:84%
but it could be that you have
a solution to a differential

01:17:56.970 --> 01:17:57.630 align:middle line:90%
equation.

01:17:57.630 --> 01:18:02.330 align:middle line:84%
This statement here is
like a standard application

01:18:02.330 --> 01:18:05.190 align:middle line:84%
to get solutions to
differential equations.

01:18:05.190 --> 01:18:07.510 align:middle line:84%
And you can use for all
kinds of other stuff.

01:18:07.510 --> 01:18:10.450 align:middle line:90%


01:18:10.450 --> 01:18:12.120 align:middle line:84%
So we'll talk about
that next time.

01:18:12.120 --> 01:18:15.988 align:middle line:90%


01:18:15.988 --> 01:18:18.030 align:middle line:84%
We'll talk about the
contracting mapping theorem.

01:18:18.030 --> 01:18:22.130 align:middle line:84%
We won't talk quite yet
about the applications.

01:18:22.130 --> 01:18:25.090 align:middle line:90%
Any questions?

01:18:25.090 --> 01:18:27.120 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

01:18:27.120 --> 01:18:31.000 align:middle line:90%